tion-7.md:1-48\",\"research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-004.md:16-62\",\"research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-005.md:22-51\",\"research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-006.md:9-31,82\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n{\"type\":\"iteration\",\"iteration\":8,\"mode\":\"research\",\"target_agent\":\"deep-research\",\"agent_definition_loaded\":true,\"resolved_route\":\"Resolved route: mode=research target_agent=deep-research\",\"run\":8,\"status\":\"complete\",\"focus\":\"Generation-bound human-auditable holdout and retrieval substrate closure\",\"findingsCount\":6,\"newInfoRatio\":0.85,\"noveltyJustification\":\"3 of 6 findings were fully new and 3 partially extended prior architecture; closing the final open question added the 0.10 simplicity bonus.\",\"keyQuestions\":[\"Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\"],\"answeredQuestions\":[\"Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\"],\"ruledOut\":[\"BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents\",\"Treating pooled recall as corpus-wide recall\",\"Semantic reranking as a baseline dependency without a same-generation labeled comparison\"],\"focusTrack\":\"retrieval-validation\",\"edgeCase\":\"contradictory-evidence\",\"toolsUsed\":[\"Read\",\"Glob\",\"Bash\",\"apply_patch\"],\"sourcesQueried\":[\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-9\",\"research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:11-282\",\"research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:375-554\",\"research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-003.md:1-103\",\"research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-006.md:1-82\",\".opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/*/{DESIGN.md,design-tokens.json,source.md}\",\"read-only in-memory holdout benchmark generation sha256:0f70d96a1e640f69eb6fdad6248b67f178926aa65ac61be1eb346646a2ffd8b4\"],\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-18T10:35:34Z\",\"durationMs\":600000,\"graphEvents\":[]}\n{\"type\":\"event\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":8,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-18T10:38:52Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-1784366607889-1j7alg\",\"generation\":1,\"event\":\"min_iterations_guard_pass\",\"iterationCount\":8,\"minIterations\":3}\n{\"type\":\"event\",\"mode\":\"research\",\"run\":8,\"timestamp\":\"2026-07-18T10:38:52Z\",\"sessionId\":\"fanout-sol-1784366607889-1j7alg\",\"generation\":1,\"event\":\"convergence_decision\",\"decision\":\"STOP\",\"stopReason\":\"converged\",\"reason\":\"all_questions_answered\",\"gateResults\":{\"convergence\":{\"pass\":true,\"reason\":\"all_questions_answered\"},\"keyQuestionCoverage\":{\"pass\":true,\"answered\":5,\"total\":5},\"sourceDiversity\":{\"pass\":true,\"code\":147,\"other\":18},\"focusAlignment\":{\"pass\":true,\"covered\":5,\"total\":5},\"singleWeakSource\":{\"pass\":true}}}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":12,"totalLines":12,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl","time":{"start":1784371314732,"end":1784371314739}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07f247c42514d540016a5b58726a6881918fd1a79b893c62ac"}},"id":"prt_f74d1801d001py6vG1gg2XUQmD","sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","messageID":"msg_f74d139cd001NFObtvGUjJPKQB"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784371314774,"sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_Hy56Y3ejF7XtOem2VTYWMBiO","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Deep Research Strategy: sk-design Styles Utilization\n2: \n3: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n4: \n5: Investigate how the existing sk-design family can exploit its large corpus of extracted real-world styles without turning retrieval into generic averaging or imposing excessive runtime and maintenance cost.\n6: \n7: ## 2. TOPIC\n8: \n9: How should the sk-design hub and the interface, foundations, motion, audit, and md-generator modes index, retrieve, and consume the ~1,290-style corpus under `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/`?\n10: \n11: <!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n12: ## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n13: - [x] Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n14: - [x] What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n15: - [x] Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\n16: - [x] What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\n17: - [x] How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n18: \n19: <!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n20: \n21: ## 4. NON-GOALS\n22: \n23: - Do not implement an index, query service, or mode integration.\n24: - Do not modify the styles corpus, sk-design skill files, or packet documents outside this lineage.\n25: - Do not evaluate the visual quality of all corpus entries individually.\n26: \n27: ## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n28: \n29: - Stop at legal convergence after at least three evidence iterations, or at ten iterations.\n30: - A legal stop requires evidence-backed answers for all five key questions, source diversity across sk-design contracts and corpus samples, and a ranked strategy table with concrete costs and risks.\n31: \n32: <!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n33: ## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n34: - Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n35: - What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n36: - Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\n37: - What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\n38: - How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n39: \n40: <!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n41: \n42: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n43: <!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n44: ## 7. WHAT WORKED\n45: - Reusing pinned corpus benchmarks and reading only the exact repository generator, crawl, and freshness anchors made the lifecycle concrete without repeating broad corpus scans. (iteration 6)\n46: - scanning every surfaced provenance record and extraction bundle converted a representative license concern into a qualified corpus-wide metadata result, while reusing iteration 6's component measurements kept cost estimates tied to repository evidence. (iteration 7)\n47: - A pooled, source-anchored holdout made false-positive mechanisms visible; in particular, explicit “no spring/no parallax” text showed why term relevance is not intent relevance. (iteration 8)\n48: \n49: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n50: \n51: <!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n52: ## 8. WHAT FAILED\n53: - The initial broad grep returned substantial unrelated stale/atomic matches; it was useful only for locating one atomic-write precedent and was not used as a ranking survey. (iteration 6)\n54: - the first URL-host parser treated Markdown link separators as URL characters and raised on a false IPv6 form; the recovered parser isolated host parsing and prevented that diagnostic from becoming a finding. (iteration 7)\n55: - Pooled recall cannot estimate unseen corpus-wide recall, and the small labels are not a substitute for a blinded benchmark. Expanding the pool would refine weights but is not necessary to choose a safe layered baseline. (iteration 8)\n56: \n57: <!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n58: \n59: <!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n60: ## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n61: ### **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n62: - What was tried: **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric.\n63: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n64: - Do NOT retry: **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric.\n65: \n66: ### **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n67: - What was tried: **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic.\n68: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n69: - Do NOT retry: **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic.\n70: \n71: ### **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n72: - What was tried: **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging.\n73: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n74: - Do NOT retry: **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging.\n75: \n76: ### A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n77: - What was tried: A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417]\n78: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n79: - Do NOT retry: A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417]\n80: \n81: ### A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n82: - What was tried: A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399]\n83: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n84: - Do NOT retry: A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399]\n85: \n86: ### A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n87: - What was tried: A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields.\n88: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n89: - Do NOT retry: A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields.\n90: \n91: ### A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n92: - What was tried: A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency.\n93: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n94: - Do NOT retry: A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency.\n95: \n96: ### Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n97: - What was tried: Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs.\n98: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n99: - Do NOT retry: Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs.\n100: \n101: ### Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n102: - What was tried: Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions.\n103: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n104: - Do NOT retry: Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions.\n105: \n106: ### BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n107: - What was tried: BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction.\n108: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n109: - Do NOT retry: BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction.\n110: \n111: ### Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n112: - What was tried: Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot.\n113: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n114: - Do NOT retry: Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot.\n115: \n116: ### Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n117: - What was tried: Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need.\n118: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n119: - Do NOT retry: Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need.\n120: \n121: ### Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified. -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n122: - What was tried: Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified.\n123: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n124: - Do NOT retry: Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified.\n125: \n126: ### Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n127: - What was tried: Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker.\n128: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n129: - Do NOT retry: Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker.\n130: \n131: ### Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence. -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n132: - What was tried: Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence.\n133: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n134: - Do NOT retry: Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence.\n135: \n136: ### Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n137: - What was tried: Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift.\n138: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n139: - Do NOT retry: Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift.\n140: \n141: ### Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n142: - What was tried: Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction.\n143: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n144: - Do NOT retry: Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction.\n145: \n146: ### Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:98-106] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n147: - What was tried: Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:98-106]\n148: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n149: - Do NOT retry: Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:98-106]\n150: \n151: ### Metadata-only final ranking; prior interface/audit evidence shows material lexical gains after deterministic eligibility. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n152: - What was tried: Metadata-only final ranking; prior interface/audit evidence shows material lexical gains after deterministic eligibility.\n153: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n154: - Do NOT retry: Metadata-only final ranking; prior interface/audit evidence shows material lexical gains after deterministic eligibility.\n155: \n156: ### Per-mode taste rules in the hub or engine: mode-supplied generic requirements preserve the hub's routing boundary. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:164-190,232-290] [INFERENCE: generic capabilities avoid central taste policy] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n157: - What was tried: Per-mode taste rules in the hub or engine: mode-supplied generic requirements preserve the hub's routing boundary. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:164-190,232-290] [INFERENCE: generic capabilities avoid central taste policy]\n158: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n159: - Do NOT retry: Per-mode taste rules in the hub or engine: mode-supplied generic requirements preserve the hub's routing boundary. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:164-190,232-290] [INFERENCE: generic capabilities avoid central taste policy]\n160: \n161: ### Promote “one ranker can be authoritative across all five modes” to exhausted; the evidence requires deterministic constraints, lexical ranking, and mode-owned judgment. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n162: - What was tried: Promote “one ranker can be authoritative across all five modes” to exhausted; the evidence requires deterministic constraints, lexical ranking, and mode-owned judgment.\n163: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n164: - Do NOT retry: Promote “one ranker can be authoritative across all five modes” to exhausted; the evidence requires deterministic constraints, lexical ranking, and mode-owned judgment.\n165: \n166: ### Promote “semantic reranking required before baseline launch” to exhausted for this decision. Reconsider only as a separately measured same-generation ablation. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n167: - What was tried: Promote “semantic reranking required before baseline launch” to exhausted for this decision. Reconsider only as a separately measured same-generation ablation.\n168: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n169: - Do NOT retry: Promote “semantic reranking required before baseline launch” to exhausted for this decision. Reconsider only as a separately measured same-generation ablation.\n170: \n171: ### Promote “watcher/daemon-based refresh for this corpus” to exhausted unless future profiling shows build/check latency above the interactive budget. -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n172: - What was tried: Promote “watcher/daemon-based refresh for this corpus” to exhausted unless future profiling shows build/check latency above the interactive budget.\n173: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n174: - Do NOT retry: Promote “watcher/daemon-based refresh for this corpus” to exhausted unless future profiling shows build/check latency above the interactive budget.\n175: \n176: ### Promote default full-corpus prompt loading to an exhausted strategy: its apparent zero build cost hides maximum recurring context cost and bypasses candidate, provenance, hydration, and coherence controls. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n177: - What was tried: Promote default full-corpus prompt loading to an exhausted strategy: its apparent zero build cost hides maximum recurring context cost and bypasses candidate, provenance, hydration, and coherence controls.\n178: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n179: - Do NOT retry: Promote default full-corpus prompt loading to an exhausted strategy: its apparent zero build cost hides maximum recurring context cost and bypasses candidate, provenance, hydration, and coherence controls.\n180: \n181: ### Semantic embeddings in the first build: semantic lift is still unmeasured on a generation-bound labeled holdout. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:531-548] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n182: - What was tried: Semantic embeddings in the first build: semantic lift is still unmeasured on a generation-bound labeled holdout. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:531-548]\n183: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n184: - Do NOT retry: Semantic embeddings in the first build: semantic lift is still unmeasured on a generation-bound labeled holdout. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:531-548]\n185: \n186: ### Semantic reranking as a baseline dependency without a same-generation labeled comparison. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n187: - What was tried: Semantic reranking as a baseline dependency without a same-generation labeled comparison.\n188: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n189: - Do NOT retry: Semantic reranking as a baseline dependency without a same-generation labeled comparison.\n190: \n191: ### Shipping semantic reranking before a labeled, same-generation comparison: storage/versioning work cannot substitute for relevance evidence. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n192: - What was tried: Shipping semantic reranking before a labeled, same-generation comparison: storage/versioning work cannot substitute for relevance evidence.\n193: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n194: - Do NOT retry: Shipping semantic reranking before a labeled, same-generation comparison: storage/versioning work cannot substitute for relevance evidence.\n195: \n196: ### Treating absent license fields as either permission or prohibition: the metadata supports only `unknown`, not a legal verdict. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n197: - What was tried: Treating absent license fields as either permission or prohibition: the metadata supports only `unknown`, not a legal verdict.\n198: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n199: - Do NOT retry: Treating absent license fields as either permission or prohibition: the metadata supports only `unknown`, not a legal verdict.\n200: \n201: ### Treating incidental temporal words in a static style as motion evidence. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n202: - What was tried: Treating incidental temporal words in a static style as motion evidence.\n203: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n204: - Do NOT retry: Treating incidental temporal words in a static style as motion evidence.\n205: \n206: ### Treating pooled recall as corpus-wide recall or this nine-candidate-per-mode pool as a universal gold standard. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n207: - What was tried: Treating pooled recall as corpus-wide recall or this nine-candidate-per-mode pool as a universal gold standard.\n208: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n209: - Do NOT retry: Treating pooled recall as corpus-wide recall or this nine-candidate-per-mode pool as a universal gold standard.\n210: \n211: ### Treating the five-query aggregate P@5 as a general corpus relevance score; the foundations and md-generator rubrics were too broad and the motion rubric had no positives. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n212: - What was tried: Treating the five-query aggregate P@5 as a general corpus relevance score; the foundations and md-generator rubrics were too broad and the motion rubric had no positives.\n213: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n214: - Do NOT retry: Treating the five-query aggregate P@5 as a general corpus relevance score; the foundations and md-generator rubrics were too broad and the motion rubric had no positives.\n215: \n216: ### Treating the secondary scan's `malformed_urls` counter as corpus evidence: the URL regex consumed Markdown's `](` separator in duplicated link syntax; direct field coverage was retained, but that counter was discarded. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n217: - What was tried: Treating the secondary scan's `malformed_urls` counter as corpus evidence: the URL regex consumed Markdown's `](` separator in duplicated link syntax; direct field coverage was retained, but that counter was discarded.\n218: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n219: - Do NOT retry: Treating the secondary scan's `malformed_urls` counter as corpus evidence: the URL regex consumed Markdown's `](` separator in duplicated link syntax; direct field coverage was retained, but that counter was discarded.\n220: \n221: ### Unbounded mixing of top-ranked styles or averaging token values. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n222: - What was tried: Unbounded mixing of top-ranked styles or averaging token values.\n223: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n224: - Do NOT retry: Unbounded mixing of top-ranked styles or averaging token values.\n225: \n226: ### Using BM25 without deterministic mode/provenance/axis eligibility, even though BM25 outperformed metadata on the discriminating lexical queries. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n227: - What was tried: Using BM25 without deterministic mode/provenance/axis eligibility, even though BM25 outperformed metadata on the discriminating lexical queries.\n228: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n229: - Do NOT retry: Using BM25 without deterministic mode/provenance/axis eligibility, even though BM25 outperformed metadata on the discriminating lexical queries.\n230: \n231: ### Using more than one study pair or any corpus synthesis in md-generator's measured phases. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n232: - What was tried: Using more than one study pair or any corpus synthesis in md-generator's measured phases.\n233: - Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n234: - Do NOT retry: Using more than one study pair or any corpus synthesis in md-generator's measured phases.\n235: \n236: <!-- /ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n237: \n238: <!-- ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n239: ## 10. RULED OUT DIRECTIONS\n240: - **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric. (iteration 3)\n241: - Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot. (iteration 3)\n242: - Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker. (iteration 3)\n243: - Treating the five-query aggregate P@5 as a general corpus relevance score; the foundations and md-generator rubrics were too broad and the motion rubric had no positives. (iteration 3)\n244: - Using BM25 without deterministic mode/provenance/axis eligibility, even though BM25 outperformed metadata on the discriminating lexical queries. (iteration 3)\n245: - **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging. (iteration 4)\n246: - Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction. (iteration 4)\n247: - Treating incidental temporal words in a static style as motion evidence. (iteration 4)\n248: - Unbounded mixing of top-ranked styles or averaging token values. (iteration 4)\n249: - Using more than one study pair or any corpus synthesis in md-generator's measured phases. (iteration 4)\n250: - **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic. (iteration 5)\n251: - A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields. (iteration 5)\n252: - A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency. (iteration 5)\n253: - Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs. (iteration 5)\n254: - Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions. (iteration 5)\n255: - A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417] (iteration 6)\n256: - A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399] (iteration 6)\n257: - Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified. (iteration 6)\n258: - Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence. (iteration 6)\n259: - Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:98-106] (iteration 6)\n260: - Per-mode taste rules in the hub or engine: mode-supplied generic requirements preserve the hub's routing boundary. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:164-190,232-290] [INFERENCE: generic capabilities avoid central taste policy] (iteration 6)\n261: - Promote “watcher/daemon-based refresh for this corpus” to exhausted unless future profiling shows build/check latency above the interactive budget. (iteration 6)\n262: - Semantic embeddings in the first build: semantic lift is still unmeasured on a generation-bound labeled holdout. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:531-548] (iteration 6)\n263: - Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need. (iteration 7)\n264: - Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift. (iteration 7)\n265: - Promote default full-corpus prompt loading to an exhausted strategy: its apparent zero build cost hides maximum recurring context cost and bypasses candidate, provenance, hydration, and coherence controls. (iteration 7)\n266: - Shipping semantic reranking before a labeled, same-generation comparison: storage/versioning work cannot substitute for relevance evidence. (iteration 7)\n267: - Treating absent license fields as either permission or prohibition: the metadata supports only `unknown`, not a legal verdict. (iteration 7)\n268: - Treating the secondary scan's `malformed_urls` counter as corpus evidence: the URL regex consumed Markdown's `](` separator in duplicated link syntax; direct field coverage was retained, but that counter was discarded. (iteration 7)\n269: - BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction. (iteration 8)\n270: - Metadata-only final ranking; prior interface/audit evidence shows material lexical gains after deterministic eligibility. (iteration 8)\n271: - Promote “one ranker can be authoritative across all five modes” to exhausted; the evidence requires deterministic constraints, lexical ranking, and mode-owned judgment. (iteration 8)\n272: - Promote “semantic reranking required before baseline launch” to exhausted for this decision. Reconsider only as a separately measured same-generation ablation. (iteration 8)\n273: - Semantic reranking as a baseline dependency without a same-generation labeled comparison. (iteration 8)\n274: - Treating pooled recall as corpus-wide recall or this nine-candidate-per-mode pool as a universal gold standard. (iteration 8)\n275: \n276: <!-- /ANCHOR:ruled-out-directions -->\n277: \n278: <!-- ANCHOR:divergence-frontier -->\n279: ## 10A. SATURATED DIRECTIONS AND DIVERGENCE FRONTIER\n280: - Completed pivots: 0\n281: - Failed pivots: 0\n282: - Audited overrides: 0\n283: - Saturated: none yet\n284: - Pivot lineage: none yet\n285: - Remaining frontier: none recorded\n286: \n287: <!-- /ANCHOR:divergence-frontier -->\n288: \n289: <!-- ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n290: ## 11A. CARRIED-FORWARD OPEN QUESTIONS\n291: - What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles? (iteration 2)\n292: - What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns? (iteration 2)\n293: - How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks? (iteration 2)\n294: - Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle? (iteration 2)\n295: - Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance? **Narrow remaining proof:** labeled mode-specific top-K relevance evaluation plus semantic-lane ablation on a quiescent snapshot. (iteration 2)\n296: \n297: <!-- /ANCHOR:carried-forward-open-questions -->\n298: \n299: <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n300: ## 11. NEXT FOCUS\n301: [All tracked questions are resolved]\n302: \n303: <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n304: <!-- MACHINE-OWNED: END -->\n305: \n306: ## 12. KNOWN CONTEXT\n307: \n308: - The parent spec identifies an unused ~1,290-style library and requires a ranked, evidence-backed strategy rather than implementation. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/spec.md:57-104]\n309: - The sk-design hub routes one public skill identity to five judgment modes and requires intake, smallest-useful-mode routing, anti-slop proof, and explicit design evidence. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:1-17]\n310: - The Spec Kit Memory trigger transport was unavailable at initialization, so packet docs and direct repository evidence are the continuity source for this lineage.\n311: - `resource-map.md` was absent from the target packet at initialization; the lineage will emit its own evidence-derived map at synthesis.\n312: \n313: ## 13. RESEARCH BOUNDARIES\n314: \n315: - Max iterations: 10\n316: - Minimum iterations before convergence: 3\n317: - Convergence threshold: 0.05\n318: - Stop policy: convergence\n319: - Per-iteration budget: 12 tool calls, 10 minutes\n320: - Persistent write root: `.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol`\n321: - Researched files are read-only; only lineage artifacts may be written.\n\n(End of file - total 321 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Deep Research Strategy: sk-design Styles Utilization\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nInvestigate how the existing sk-design family can exploit its large corpus of extracted real-world styles without turning retrieval into generic averaging or imposing excessive runtime and maintenance cost.\n\n## 2. TOPIC\n\nHow should the sk-design hub and the interface, foundations, motion, audit, and md-generator modes index, retrieve, and consume the ~1,290-style corpus under `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/`?\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [x] Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n- [x] What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n- [x] Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\n- [x] What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\n- [x] How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md","text":"# Deep Research Strategy: sk-design Styles Utilization\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nInvestigate how the existing sk-design family can exploit its large corpus of extracted real-world styles without turning retrieval into generic averaging or imposing excessive runtime and maintenance cost.\n\n## 2. TOPIC\n\nHow should the sk-design hub and the interface, foundations, motion, audit, and md-generator modes index, retrieve, and consume the ~1,290-style corpus under `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/`?\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n## 3. KEY QUESTIONS (remaining)\n- [x] Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n- [x] What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n- [x] Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\n- [x] What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\n- [x] How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:key-questions -->\n\n## 4. NON-GOALS\n\n- Do not implement an index, query service, or mode integration.\n- Do not modify the styles corpus, sk-design skill files, or packet documents outside this lineage.\n- Do not evaluate the visual quality of all corpus entries individually.\n\n## 5. STOP CONDITIONS\n\n- Stop at legal convergence after at least three evidence iterations, or at ten iterations.\n- A legal stop requires evidence-backed answers for all five key questions, source diversity across sk-design contracts and corpus samples, and a ranked strategy table with concrete costs and risks.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n## 6. ANSWERED QUESTIONS\n- Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n- What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n- Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\n- What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\n- How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:answered-questions -->\n\n<!-- MACHINE-OWNED: START -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n## 7. WHAT WORKED\n- Reusing pinned corpus benchmarks and reading only the exact repository generator, crawl, and freshness anchors made the lifecycle concrete without repeating broad corpus scans. (iteration 6)\n- scanning every surfaced provenance record and extraction bundle converted a representative license concern into a qualified corpus-wide metadata result, while reusing iteration 6's component measurements kept cost estimates tied to repository evidence. (iteration 7)\n- A pooled, source-anchored holdout made false-positive mechanisms visible; in particular, explicit “no spring/no parallax” text showed why term relevance is not intent relevance. (iteration 8)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-worked -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n## 8. WHAT FAILED\n- The initial broad grep returned substantial unrelated stale/atomic matches; it was useful only for locating one atomic-write precedent and was not used as a ranking survey. (iteration 6)\n- the first URL-host parser treated Markdown link separators as URL characters and raised on a false IPv6 form; the recovered parser isolated host parsing and prevented that diagnostic from becoming a finding. (iteration 7)\n- Pooled recall cannot estimate unseen corpus-wide recall, and the small labels are not a substitute for a blinded benchmark. Expanding the pool would refine weights but is not necessary to choose a safe layered baseline. (iteration 8)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:what-failed -->\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:exhausted-approaches -->\n## 9. EXHAUSTED APPROACHES (do not retry)\n### **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric.\n\n### **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic.\n\n### **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging.\n\n### A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417]\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417]\n\n### A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399]\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399]\n\n### A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields.\n\n### A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency.\n\n### Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs.\n\n### Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions. -- BLOCKED (iteration 5, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions.\n\n### BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction. -- BLOCKED (iteration 8, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction.\n\n### Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot.\n\n### Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need.\n\n### Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified. -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified.\n\n### Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker. -- BLOCKED (iteration 3, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker.\n\n### Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence. -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence.\n\n### Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift. -- BLOCKED (iteration 7, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift.\n\n### Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction. -- BLOCKED (iteration 4, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction.\n- Why blocked: Repeated iteration evidence ruled this direction out.\n- Do NOT retry: Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction.\n\n### Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:98-106] -- BLOCKED (iteration 6, 1 attempts)\n- What was tried: Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-desig