nd corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\",\n109:       \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n110:       \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n111:       \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n112:       \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n113:       \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n114:       \"resolvedAtIteration\": 6\n115:     },\n116:     {\n117:       \"id\": \"question-10-how-should-utilization-strategies-rank-by-leverage-versus-build-cost-after-accou\",\n118:       \"inboxId\": null,\n119:       \"text\": \"How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\",\n120:       \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n121:       \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n122:       \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n123:       \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n124:       \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n125:       \"resolvedAtIteration\": 7\n126:     }\n127:   ],\n128:   \"carriedForwardOpenQuestions\": [\n129:     {\n130:       \"text\": \"What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\",\n131:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n132:       \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n133:     },\n134:     {\n135:       \"text\": \"What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\",\n136:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n137:       \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n138:     },\n139:     {\n140:       \"text\": \"How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\",\n141:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n142:       \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n143:     },\n144:     {\n145:       \"text\": \"Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\",\n146:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n147:       \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n148:     },\n149:     {\n150:       \"text\": \"Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance? **Narrow remaining proof:** labeled mode-specific top-K relevance evaluation plus semantic-lane ablation on a quiescent snapshot.\",\n151:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n152:       \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n153:     }\n154:   ],\n155:   \"uncoveredQuestions\": [],\n156:   \"keyFindings\": [\n157:     {\n158:       \"id\": \"finding-1-2-a-style-is-a-uniform-six-artifact-bundle-but-the-artifact-classes-differ-sharply\",\n159:       \"text\": \"**A style is a uniform six-artifact bundle, but the artifact classes differ sharply in context cost.** At the stable 977-bundle measurement point, all 977 bundles contained `DESIGN.md`, `design-tokens.json`, `css-variables.css`, `tailwind-v4.css`, `source.md`, and one `*-canonical.json`, totaling 85,374,474 bytes. Median sizes were 51,109 bytes for canonical JSON, 19,584 for `DESIGN.md`, 9,936 for design tokens, 2,119 for CSS variables, 1,555 for Tailwind, and 780 for provenance. The representative source file explicitly enumerates the five generated siblings; `source.md` itself is the sixth artifact. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12] [INFERENCE: deterministic byte and completeness aggregation over the 977 `*/DESIGN.md`-anchored bundles]\",\n160:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n161:       \"sources\": [\n162:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n163:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n164:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n165:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n166:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n167:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n168:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n169:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n170:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n171:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n172:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n173:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n174:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n175:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n176:       ]\n177:     },\n178:     {\n179:       \"id\": \"finding-1-9-audit-retrieve-the-selected-reference-s-do-don-t-constraints-provenance-and-rele\",\n180:       \"text\": \"**audit:** retrieve the selected reference's do/don't constraints, provenance, and relevant token slices as comparison evidence, not as a replacement for target evidence; the contract owns slop/token-misuse detection and requires evidence-specific audit resources. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:95-115]\",\n181:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n182:       \"sources\": [\n183:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n184:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n185:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n186:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n187:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n188:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n189:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n190:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n191:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n192:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n193:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n194:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n195:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n196:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n197:       ]\n198:     },\n199:     {\n200:       \"id\": \"finding-1-5-existing-contracts-imply-mode-specific-consumption-rather-than-one-universal-ret\",\n201:       \"text\": \"**Existing contracts imply mode-specific consumption rather than one universal retrieval payload.** The hub should route and carry only a compact candidate manifest because it explicitly owns no per-mode logic; its smallest-useful-mode policy is already the first relevance filter. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:140-142] The provisional mode mapping is:\",\n202:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n203:       \"sources\": [\n204:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n205:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n206:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n207:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n208:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n209:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n210:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n211:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n212:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n213:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n214:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n215:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n216:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n217:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n218:       ]\n219:     },\n220:     {\n221:       \"id\": \"finding-1-7-foundations-retrieve-axis-specific-design-tokens-json-slices-color-type-layout-s\",\n222:       \"text\": \"**foundations:** retrieve axis-specific `design-tokens.json` slices (color, type, layout/spacing), optionally joined to the selected `DESIGN.md` rationale; its router is explicitly axis-based and permits multi-axis loading only when the task needs it. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:85-103]\",\n223:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n224:       \"sources\": [\n225:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n226:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n227:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n228:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n229:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n230:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n231:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n232:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n233:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n234:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n235:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n236:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n237:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n238:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n239:       ]\n240:     },\n241:     {\n242:       \"id\": \"finding-1-6-interface-load-one-coherent-candidate-s-design-md-plus-source-md-as-a-grounding-\",\n243:       \"text\": \"**interface:** load one coherent candidate's `DESIGN.md` plus `source.md` as a grounding reference, then critique/deviate rather than copy; the contract asks for real-system grounding and says a real-world reference is one reference, never copied. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90]\",\n244:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n245:       \"sources\": [\n246:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n247:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n248:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n249:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n250:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n251:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n252:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n253:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n254:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n255:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n256:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n257:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n258:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n259:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n260:       ]\n261:     },\n262:     {\n263:       \"id\": \"finding-1-10-md-generator-do-not-let-corpus-retrieval-override-live-measured-extraction-use-a\",\n264:       \"text\": \"**md-generator:** do not let corpus retrieval override live measured extraction; use at most one corpus pair for STUDY/format calibration because this mode captures and validates source truth and its examples are explicitly one-at-a-time study artifacts. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:109-122]\",\n265:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n266:       \"sources\": [\n267:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n268:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n269:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n270:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n271:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n272:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n273:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n274:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n275:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n276:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n277:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n278:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n279:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n280:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n281:       ]\n282:     },\n283:     {\n284:       \"id\": \"finding-1-8-motion-retrieve-only-motion-bearing-fields-or-matching-narrative-sections-when-p\",\n285:       \"text\": \"**motion:** retrieve only motion-bearing fields or matching narrative sections when present; otherwise do not load a style merely because it matches static aesthetics, because the contract routes by temporal concern and makes static-token coordination on-demand. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:97-113]\",\n286:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n287:       \"sources\": [\n288:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n289:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n290:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n291:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n292:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n293:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n294:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n295:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n296:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n297:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n298:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n299:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n300:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n301:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n302:       ]\n303:     },\n304:     {\n305:       \"id\": \"finding-1-11-provenance-is-present-but-the-representative-metadata-is-not-a-complete-rights-r\",\n306:       \"text\": \"**Provenance is present, but the representative metadata is not a complete rights record.** Kobu's `source.md` records a Refero style URL, original site, screenshot, style UUID, and capture timestamp, but no explicit license or allowed-use field. Retrieval results therefore need provenance surfaced alongside every candidate, and later research must test license-field coverage corpus-wide rather than assuming a reference is reusable because it is indexed. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:3-12] [INFERENCE: absence of an explicit license field in the representative provenance record limits what can be concluded about reuse rights]\",\n307:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n308:       \"sources\": [\n309:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n310:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n311:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n312:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n313:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n314:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n315:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n316:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n317:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n318:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n319:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n320:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n321:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n322:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n323:       ]\n324:     },\n325:     {\n326:       \"id\": \"finding-1-1-the-corpus-was-actively-growing-during-the-iteration-so-its-cardinality-is-not-p\",\n327:       \"text\": \"**The corpus was actively growing during the iteration, so its cardinality is not presently a stable indexing input.** Three read-only snapshots observed 974, then 977, then 981 complete style bundles; the final snapshot at `2026-07-18T09:31:30.875369Z` showed newly modified bundles arriving roughly every 9–10 seconds. This conflicts with, but may be progressing toward, the prompt's approximately 1,290-style estimate. A build should pin a revision or wait for a quiescence window before publishing count/checksum metadata. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24] [INFERENCE: deterministic read-only inventories of `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/*/DESIGN.md` during this iteration, plus bundle mtimes from the final snapshot]\",\n328:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n329:       \"sources\": [\n330:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n331:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n332:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n333:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n334:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n335:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n336:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n337:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n338:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n339:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n340:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n341:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n342:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n343:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n344:       ]\n345:     },\n346:     {\n347:       \"id\": \"finding-1-4-the-token-schema-is-regular-enough-for-a-compact-structural-index-without-flatte\",\n348:       \"text\": \"**The token schema is regular enough for a compact structural index without flattening every value into embeddings.** All 977 sampled `design-tokens.json` files parsed successfully. The three dominant top-level shapes covered 961/977 bundles and shared `$extensions`, `color`, `font`, `spacing`, `surface`, and `typography`, with `radius` and/or `shadow` as the principal variations. The smallest sample has two colors and one font, while the largest begins with a much denser semantic palette; this makes per-axis counts, names, descriptions, and provenance useful deterministic ranking features. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-20] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100] [INFERENCE: JSON validation and top-level-shape aggregation over all 977 measured token documents]\",\n349:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n350:       \"sources\": [\n351:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n352:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n353:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n354:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n355:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n356:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n357:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n358:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n359:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n360:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n361:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n362:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n363:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n364:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n365:       ]\n366:     },\n367:     {\n368:       \"id\": \"finding-1-3-the-two-most-useful-retrieval-payloads-serve-different-purposes-design-md-preser\",\n369:       \"text\": \"**The two most useful retrieval payloads serve different purposes: `DESIGN.md` preserves a coherent design identity, while `design-tokens.json` supports deterministic field-level filtering.** Across the 977-bundle snapshot, `DESIGN.md` ranged from 169 to 537 lines (median 373), while token documents ranged from 46 to 667 scalar leaves (median 202). Kobu's reference ties its aesthetic thesis to named colors, typography, spacing, components, and explicit do/don't constraints; the compact 19–86 JSON expresses the same machine-readable token primitives plus extraction metadata. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:159-177] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-20] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:43-89] [INFERENCE: line and scalar-leaf distributions from all 977 measured bundles]\",\n370:       \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n371:       \"sources\": [\n372:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n373:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n374:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n375:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n376:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n377:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n378:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n379:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n380:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n381:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n382:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n383:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n384:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n385:         \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n386:       ]\n387:     },\n388:     {\n389:       \"id\": \"finding-2-3-a-compact-committed-retrieval-manifest-is-cheap-enough-to-make-the-deterministic\",\n390:       \"text\": \"**A compact committed retrieval manifest is cheap enough to make the deterministic first stage, but static metadata alone has inadequate free-text recall.** A prototype record containing id, title, up to 12 headings, token axes, artifact sizes, and exact path serialized to 502,895 bytes (486.4 bytes/style) for 1,034 styles and took 171.1 ms to derive while parsing tokens. Scanning that compact projection took about 0.95–1.08 ms/query, but exact two-term tests for `brutalist editorial`, `playful colorful`, and `reduced motion` returned zero because those attributes occur in body prose rather than titles/headings. Static-only is therefore appropriate for exact eligibility/provenance/axis filtering and deterministic candidate narrowing, not final relevance ranking unless it duplicates enough prose to cease being compact. [INFERENCE: read-only Python compact-manifest benchmark over 1,034 captured bundles; compared against the same snapshot's full `DESIGN.md` bodies]\",\n391:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n392:       \"sources\": [\n393:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n394:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n395:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n396:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n397:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n398:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n399:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n400:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n401:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n402:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n403:         \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n404:       ]\n405:     },\n406:     {\n407:       \"id\": \"finding-2-4-a-queryable-sqlite-token-lexical-store-gives-excellent-query-latency-and-express\",\n408:       \"text\": \"**A queryable SQLite token/lexical store gives excellent query latency and expressiveness, but its footprint, native dependency, and freshness obligations make it a derived accelerator.** An in-memory table plus FTS5 index over all 1,034 style bodies ingested in 179.7 ms, occupied 29,093,888 SQLite page bytes, returned top-10 BM25 results in 0.054–0.203 ms for the three test queries, and ran a structured two-axis filter in 0.145 ms. The repository implementation likewise depends on `better-sqlite3`, probes both the FTS5 compile option and table presence, sanitizes lexical terms, weights BM25 columns, and fails open when FTS5 is unavailable. A store can support exact token/provenance filters and ranked lexical search, but it should expose its manifest generation/hash and rebuild from checked artifacts rather than be committed as canonical state. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:9-14,96-143,150-205,207-252] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-130] [INFERENCE: read-only in-memory SQLite benchmark over the pinned 1,034-document snapshot]\",\n409:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n410:       \"sources\": [\n411:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n412:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n413:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n414:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n415:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n416:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n417:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n418:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n419:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n420:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n421:         \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n422:       ]\n423:     },\n424:     {\n425:       \"id\": \"finding-2-5-on-demand-grep-is-a-credible-zero-build-fallback-and-freshness-oracle-but-not-th\",\n426:       \"text\": \"**On-demand grep is a credible zero-build fallback and freshness oracle, but not the default substrate.** Each test query deterministically read 20,378,783 bytes across 1,034 `DESIGN.md` files and completed in 32.71–33.35 ms on the warm local checkout, finding 34, 22, and 29 all-term matches respectively. That cost is acceptable for diagnosis or when a derived index is stale/unavailable, and grep reads source truth immediately; however, every query repeats the full scan, lexical matches are unranked without additional code, structured token/provenance predicates require joins to other artifacts, and indiscriminate snippet/body loading would violate the hub's smallest-useful-mode discipline. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:140-142,168-184] [INFERENCE: read-only full-file scan benchmark over 20,378,783 bytes of `DESIGN.md` content]\",\n427:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n428:       \"sources\": [\n429:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n430:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n431:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n432:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n433:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n434:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n435:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n436:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n437:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n438:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n439:         \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n440:       ]\n441:     },\n442:     {\n443:       \"id\": \"finding-2-6-the-best-current-balance-is-a-layered-hybrid-committed-manifest-deterministic-fi\",\n444:       \"text\": \"**The best current balance is a layered hybrid: committed manifest → deterministic filters → lexical rank → optional semantic rerank → mode-specific hydration.** The committed manifest should join crawl state with per-artifact content hashes, title/summary, token axes and counts, available motion/do-don't sections, provenance/license-known state, mode eligibility, and byte costs. Deterministic filters should first exclude pending/stale/unlicensed-for-the-request candidates and constrain mode/axis. FTS5/BM25 should rank body text; semantic ranking should be optional, versioned, and only break lexical/structured ambiguity because the repository's semantic lane adds model/runtime dependencies while its hybrid API already supports separately switchable vector, FTS, BM25, graph, and trigger channels. The hub receives only candidate cards; hydration then preserves one coherent `DESIGN.md` plus provenance for interface, token-axis slices for foundations, motion sections only for motion, do/don't plus provenance for audit, and at most one calibration pair for md-generator. This keeps retrieval broad but context narrow and preserves each mode rather than flattening their logic. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:140-142,168-184,201-204] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122] [INFERENCE: synthesis of findings 1-5 and iteration-1 mode-consumption evidence]\",\n445:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n446:       \"sources\": [\n447:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n448:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n449:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n450:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n451:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n452:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n453:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n454:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n455:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n456:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n457:         \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n458:       ]\n459:     },\n460:     {\n461:       \"id\": \"finding-2-2-the-current-crawl-state-proves-why-a-hand-maintained-static-index-is-insufficien\",\n462:       \"text\": \"**The current crawl state proves why a hand-maintained static index is insufficient and why every published index needs freshness metadata.** The manual `styles/README.md` says 50 of 1,290 styles, while the read-only snapshot found 1,034 `DESIGN.md` bundles and the 1,290-row crawl manifest contained 1,034 `captured` plus 256 `pending` rows. The existing manifest is useful provenance/freshness input (`uuid`, URL, `lastmod`, slug, status, capture time, error), but it has no retrieval attributes, artifact hashes, token-axis statistics, or mode eligibility. This contradiction is resolved as manual-index staleness, not corpus uncertainty. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-12] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-18] [INFERENCE: read-only Python snapshot and manifest aggregation over `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/` at 2026-07-18T09:40Z]\",\n463:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n464:       \"sources\": [\n465:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n466:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n467:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n468:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n469:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n470:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n471:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n472:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n473:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n474:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n475:         \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n476:       ]\n477:     },\n478:     {\n479:       \"id\": \"finding-2-1-the-strongest-repository-native-precedent-is-a-checked-source-manifest-plus-a-re\",\n480:       \"text\": \"**The strongest repository-native precedent is a checked source manifest plus a rebuildable query projection, not a database as source of truth.** The advisor's `leaf-manifest.json` is generated, must be byte-stable under `--check`, and authorizes exact routable paths; its SQLite graph separately indexes checked `graph-metadata.json`, records source paths and content hashes, and reports changed or missing sources by recomputing SHA-256. The styles harness already has the beginnings of the same split: committed `_manifest.json` is lastmod-keyed crawl state, while captured artifacts remain canonical. A styles retrieval manifest should therefore be committed and checkable, while any SQLite/FTS or embedding store should be disposable and generation-bound. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:87-99] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:23-28,37-49,91-96]\",\n481:       \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n482:       \"sources\": [\n483:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n484:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n485:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n486:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n487:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n488:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n489:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n490:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n491:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n492:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n493:         \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n494:       ]\n495:     },\n496:     {\n497:       \"id\": \"finding-3-2-bm25-materially-improved-the-two-discriminating-lexical-queries-while-determinis\",\n498:       \"text\": \"**BM25 materially improved the two discriminating lexical queries, while deterministic metadata remained useful for eligibility rather than final ranking.** Interface precision@5 rose from 0.20 to 0.80 and audit from 0.00 to 0.60; the five-query mean rose from 0.44 to 0.68. Foundations tied at 1.00 because 681 rows met a broad rubric, while md-generator tied at 1.00 because all 1,091 rows did, so those ties demonstrate structural eligibility but provide almost no ranking discrimination. This supports deterministic filters followed by lexical ranking, not BM25-only or metadata-only retrieval. [INFERENCE: top-5 results and rubric counts in the pinned ablation] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:20-26]\",\n499:       \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n500:       \"sources\": [\n501:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",\n502:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-4`\",\n503:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:11-102`\",\n504:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:8-140,375-480`\",\n505:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-3.md:6-53`\",\n506:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:14-95`\",\n507:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90`\",\n508:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n509:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113`\",\n510:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n511:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n512:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145`\",\n513:         \"Read-only in-memory snapshot, deterministic-rank, SQLite FTS5/BM25, candidate-card, and hydration-byte output for snapshot `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`.\"\n514:       ]\n515:     },\n516:     {\n517:       \"id\": \"finding-3-4-candidate-discovery-can-stay-cheap-in-context-while-hydration-remains-mode-propo\",\n518:       \"text\": \"**Candidate discovery can stay cheap in context while hydration remains mode-proportional.** Five candidate cards cost 1,357–1,582 bytes per mode (7,302 bytes across all five queries). Selected hydration ranged from 845 bytes for motion fragments to 16,471 bytes for one md-generator calibration pair, with a 4,803-byte median and 40,088 bytes across five independently selected mode payloads. These measurements validate candidate-card-first delivery and show why full-document hydration belongs only to coherent-reference modes. [INFERENCE: UTF-8 byte measurement of serialized top-5 cards and selected payloads from the pinned snapshot] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122]\",\n519:       \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n520:       \"sources\": [\n521:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",\n522:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-4`\",\n523:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:11-102`\",\n524:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:8-140,375-480`\",\n525:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-3.md:6-53`\",\n526:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:14-95`\",\n527:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90`\",\n528:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n529:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113`\",\n530:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n531:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n532:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145`\",\n533:         \"Read-only in-memory snapshot, deterministic-rank, SQLite FTS5/BM25, candidate-card, and hydration-byte output for snapshot `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`.\"\n534:       ]\n535:     },\n536:     {\n537:       \"id\": \"finding-3-5-semantic-lift-remains-unmeasured-not-negative-repository-evidence-establishes-a-\",\n538:       \"text\": \"**Semantic lift remains unmeasured, not negative.** Repository evidence establishes a separately switchable semantic/vector lane, but this lineage has no verified corpus-specific labeled embedding index bound to the pinned generation. Running a different or newly built generation would break the controlled comparison, so no semantic result was fabricated. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:22-26] [INFERENCE: absence of a verified generation-bound semantic result in the lineage evidence]\",\n539:       \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n540:       \"sources\": [\n541:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",\n542:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-4`\",\n543:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:11-102`\",\n544:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:8-140,375-480`\",\n545:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-3.md:6-53`\",\n546:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:14-95`\",\n547:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90`\",\n548:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n549:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113`\",\n550:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n551:         \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n552:         \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145`\",\n553:         \"Read-only in-memory snapshot, deterministic-rank, SQLite FTS5/BM25, candidate-card, and hydration-byte output for snapshot `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`.\"\n554:       ]\n555:     },\n556:     {\n557:       \"id\": \"finding-3-1-the-comparison-used-a-stable-content-addressed-generation-rather-than-a-moving-d\",\n558:       \"text\": \"**The comparison used a stable, content-addressed generation rather than a moving directory count.** The snapshot contained 1,091 `DESIGN.md` documents and their 2,182 token/provenance siblings (3,273 files, 34,241,583 bytes); pre/post path, size, and mtime fingerprints matched, and the loaded bytes produced snapshot id `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`. This removes the active-crawl ambiguity for this ablation without claiming that 1,091 is the final corpus size. [INFERENCE: read-only snapshot fingerprint and SHA-256 aggregation performed before ranking]\",\n559:       \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n560:       \"sources\": [\n561:         \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",\n\n(Output capped at 50 KB. Showing lines 1-561. Use offset=562 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-1784366607889-1j7alg\",\n  \"parentSessionId\": null,\n  \"lineageMode\": \"new\",\n  \"generation\": 1,\n  \"continuedFromRun\": null,\n  \"terminalStop\": null,\n  \"keyQuestions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-6-which-retrieval-substrate-or-layered-combination-of-substrates-best-balances-rel\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 8,\n      \"resolved\": true\n    },","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json","text":"{\n  \"sessionId\": \"fanout-sol-1784366607889-1j7alg\",\n  \"parentSessionId\": null,\n  \"lineageMode\": \"new\",\n  \"generation\": 1,\n  \"continuedFromRun\": null,\n  \"terminalStop\": null,\n  \"keyQuestions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-6-which-retrieval-substrate-or-layered-combination-of-substrates-best-balances-rel\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 8,\n      \"resolved\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-7-what-should-the-hub-and-each-of-the-five-modes-consume-and-when-should-a-task-re\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 4,\n      \"resolved\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-8-which-anti-slop-rules-and-proof-gates-keep-outputs-distinctive-rather-than-avera\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 5,\n      \"resolved\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-9-what-index-build-query-refresh-validation-and-corpus-change-tooling-is-justified\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 6,\n      \"resolved\": true\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-10-how-should-utilization-strategies-rank-by-leverage-versus-build-cost-after-accou\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 7,\n      \"resolved\": true\n    }\n  ],\n  \"openQuestions\": [],\n  \"resolvedQuestions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-6-which-retrieval-substrate-or-layered-combination-of-substrates-best-balances-rel\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 8\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-7-what-should-the-hub-and-each-of-the-five-modes-consume-and-when-should-a-task-re\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 4\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-8-which-anti-slop-rules-and-proof-gates-keep-outputs-distinctive-rather-than-avera\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 5\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-9-what-index-build-query-refresh-validation-and-corpus-change-tooling-is-justified\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 6\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"question-10-how-should-utilization-strategies-rank-by-leverage-versus-build-cost-after-accou\",\n      \"inboxId\": null,\n      \"text\": \"How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\",\n      \"origin\": \"legacy-import\",\n      \"source\": \"key-questions\",\n      \"injectedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"promotedQuestionId\": null,\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 0,\n      \"resolvedAtIteration\": 7\n    }\n  ],\n  \"carriedForwardOpenQuestions\": [\n    {\n      \"text\": \"What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"text\": \"What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"text\": \"How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"text\": \"Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"text\": \"Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance? **Narrow remaining proof:** labeled mode-specific top-K relevance evaluation plus semantic-lane ablation on a quiescent snapshot.\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"source\": \"iteration-markdown\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"uncoveredQuestions\": [],\n  \"keyFindings\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-2-a-style-is-a-uniform-six-artifact-bundle-but-the-artifact-classes-differ-sharply\",\n      \"text\": \"**A style is a uniform six-artifact bundle, but the artifact classes differ sharply in context cost.** At the stable 977-bundle measurement point, all 977 bundles contained `DESIGN.md`, `design-tokens.json`, `css-variables.css`, `tailwind-v4.css`, `source.md`, and one `*-canonical.json`, totaling 85,374,474 bytes. Median sizes were 51,109 bytes for canonical JSON, 19,584 for `DESIGN.md`, 9,936 for design tokens, 2,119 for CSS variables, 1,555 for Tailwind, and 780 for provenance. The representative source file explicitly enumerates the five generated siblings; `source.md` itself is the sixth artifact. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12] [INFERENCE: deterministic byte and completeness aggregation over the 977 `*/DESIGN.md`-anchored bundles]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-9-audit-retrieve-the-selected-reference-s-do-don-t-constraints-provenance-and-rele\",\n      \"text\": \"**audit:** retrieve the selected reference's do/don't constraints, provenance, and relevant token slices as comparison evidence, not as a replacement for target evidence; the contract owns slop/token-misuse detection and requires evidence-specific audit resources. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:95-115]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-5-existing-contracts-imply-mode-specific-consumption-rather-than-one-universal-ret\",\n      \"text\": \"**Existing contracts imply mode-specific consumption rather than one universal retrieval payload.** The hub should route and carry only a compact candidate manifest because it explicitly owns no per-mode logic; its smallest-useful-mode policy is already the first relevance filter. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:140-142] The provisional mode mapping is:\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-7-foundations-retrieve-axis-specific-design-tokens-json-slices-color-type-layout-s\",\n      \"text\": \"**foundations:** retrieve axis-specific `design-tokens.json` slices (color, type, layout/spacing), optionally joined to the selected `DESIGN.md` rationale; its router is explicitly axis-based and permits multi-axis loading only when the task needs it. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:85-103]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-6-interface-load-one-coherent-candidate-s-design-md-plus-source-md-as-a-grounding-\",\n      \"text\": \"**interface:** load one coherent candidate's `DESIGN.md` plus `source.md` as a grounding reference, then critique/deviate rather than copy; the contract asks for real-system grounding and says a real-world reference is one reference, never copied. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-10-md-generator-do-not-let-corpus-retrieval-override-live-measured-extraction-use-a\",\n      \"text\": \"**md-generator:** do not let corpus retrieval override live measured extraction; use at most one corpus pair for STUDY/format calibration because this mode captures and validates source truth and its examples are explicitly one-at-a-time study artifacts. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:109-122]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-8-motion-retrieve-only-motion-bearing-fields-or-matching-narrative-sections-when-p\",\n      \"text\": \"**motion:** retrieve only motion-bearing fields or matching narrative sections when present; otherwise do not load a style merely because it matches static aesthetics, because the contract routes by temporal concern and makes static-token coordination on-demand. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:97-113]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-11-provenance-is-present-but-the-representative-metadata-is-not-a-complete-rights-r\",\n      \"text\": \"**Provenance is present, but the representative metadata is not a complete rights record.** Kobu's `source.md` records a Refero style URL, original site, screenshot, style UUID, and capture timestamp, but no explicit license or allowed-use field. Retrieval results therefore need provenance surfaced alongside every candidate, and later research must test license-field coverage corpus-wide rather than assuming a reference is reusable because it is indexed. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:3-12] [INFERENCE: absence of an explicit license field in the representative provenance record limits what can be concluded about reuse rights]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-1-the-corpus-was-actively-growing-during-the-iteration-so-its-cardinality-is-not-p\",\n      \"text\": \"**The corpus was actively growing during the iteration, so its cardinality is not presently a stable indexing input.** Three read-only snapshots observed 974, then 977, then 981 complete style bundles; the final snapshot at `2026-07-18T09:31:30.875369Z` showed newly modified bundles arriving roughly every 9–10 seconds. This conflicts with, but may be progressing toward, the prompt's approximately 1,290-style estimate. A build should pin a revision or wait for a quiescence window before publishing count/checksum metadata. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24] [INFERENCE: deterministic read-only inventories of `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/*/DESIGN.md` during this iteration, plus bundle mtimes from the final snapshot]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-4-the-token-schema-is-regular-enough-for-a-compact-structural-index-without-flatte\",\n      \"text\": \"**The token schema is regular enough for a compact structural index without flattening every value into embeddings.** All 977 sampled `design-tokens.json` files parsed successfully. The three dominant top-level shapes covered 961/977 bundles and shared `$extensions`, `color`, `font`, `spacing`, `surface`, and `typography`, with `radius` and/or `shadow` as the principal variations. The smallest sample has two colors and one font, while the largest begins with a much denser semantic palette; this makes per-axis counts, names, descriptions, and provenance useful deterministic ranking features. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-20] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-80] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100] [INFERENCE: JSON validation and top-level-shape aggregation over all 977 measured token documents]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-1-3-the-two-most-useful-retrieval-payloads-serve-different-purposes-design-md-preser\",\n      \"text\": \"**The two most useful retrieval payloads serve different purposes: `DESIGN.md` preserves a coherent design identity, while `design-tokens.json` supports deterministic field-level filtering.** Across the 977-bundle snapshot, `DESIGN.md` ranged from 169 to 537 lines (median 373), while token documents ranged from 46 to 667 scalar leaves (median 202). Kobu's reference ties its aesthetic thesis to named colors, typography, spacing, components, and explicit do/don't constraints; the compact 19–86 JSON expresses the same machine-readable token primitives plus extraction metadata. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-18] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:159-177] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-20] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:43-89] [INFERENCE: line and scalar-leaf distributions from all 977 measured bundles]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 1,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-1.md:16-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:13-15,140-184,203-204`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:16-17,71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/DESIGN.md:1-180`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/kobu/source.md:1-12`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/19-86/design-tokens.json:1-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/base44/design-tokens.json:1-140`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/clickup/design-tokens.json:1-100`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/column/DESIGN.md:1-100`\",\n        \"Read-only Python inventory outputs for bundle counts, completeness, byte/line/leaf distributions, JSON validity, schema shapes, and mtimes.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-2-3-a-compact-committed-retrieval-manifest-is-cheap-enough-to-make-the-deterministic\",\n      \"text\": \"**A compact committed retrieval manifest is cheap enough to make the deterministic first stage, but static metadata alone has inadequate free-text recall.** A prototype record containing id, title, up to 12 headings, token axes, artifact sizes, and exact path serialized to 502,895 bytes (486.4 bytes/style) for 1,034 styles and took 171.1 ms to derive while parsing tokens. Scanning that compact projection took about 0.95–1.08 ms/query, but exact two-term tests for `brutalist editorial`, `playful colorful`, and `reduced motion` returned zero because those attributes occur in body prose rather than titles/headings. Static-only is therefore appropriate for exact eligibility/provenance/axis filtering and deterministic candidate narrowing, not final relevance ranking unless it duplicates enough prose to cease being compact. [INFERENCE: read-only Python compact-manifest benchmark over 1,034 captured bundles; compared against the same snapshot's full `DESIGN.md` bodies]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n        \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-2-4-a-queryable-sqlite-token-lexical-store-gives-excellent-query-latency-and-express\",\n      \"text\": \"**A queryable SQLite token/lexical store gives excellent query latency and expressiveness, but its footprint, native dependency, and freshness obligations make it a derived accelerator.** An in-memory table plus FTS5 index over all 1,034 style bodies ingested in 179.7 ms, occupied 29,093,888 SQLite page bytes, returned top-10 BM25 results in 0.054–0.203 ms for the three test queries, and ran a structured two-axis filter in 0.145 ms. The repository implementation likewise depends on `better-sqlite3`, probes both the FTS5 compile option and table presence, sanitizes lexical terms, weights BM25 columns, and fails open when FTS5 is unavailable. A store can support exact token/provenance filters and ranked lexical search, but it should expose its manifest generation/hash and rebuild from checked artifacts rather than be committed as canonical state. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:9-14,96-143,150-205,207-252] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-130] [INFERENCE: read-only in-memory SQLite benchmark over the pinned 1,034-document snapshot]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n        \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-2-5-on-demand-grep-is-a-credible-zero-build-fallback-and-freshness-oracle-but-not-th\",\n      \"text\": \"**On-demand grep is a credible zero-build fallback and freshness oracle, but not the default substrate.** Each test query deterministically read 20,378,783 bytes across 1,034 `DESIGN.md` files and completed in 32.71–33.35 ms on the warm local checkout, finding 34, 22, and 29 all-term matches respectively. That cost is acceptable for diagnosis or when a derived index is stale/unavailable, and grep reads source truth immediately; however, every query repeats the full scan, lexical matches are unranked without additional code, structured token/provenance predicates require joins to other artifacts, and indiscriminate snippet/body loading would violate the hub's smallest-useful-mode discipline. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:140-142,168-184] [INFERENCE: read-only full-file scan benchmark over 20,378,783 bytes of `DESIGN.md` content]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n        \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-2-6-the-best-current-balance-is-a-layered-hybrid-committed-manifest-deterministic-fi\",\n      \"text\": \"**The best current balance is a layered hybrid: committed manifest → deterministic filters → lexical rank → optional semantic rerank → mode-specific hydration.** The committed manifest should join crawl state with per-artifact content hashes, title/summary, token axes and counts, available motion/do-don't sections, provenance/license-known state, mode eligibility, and byte costs. Deterministic filters should first exclude pending/stale/unlicensed-for-the-request candidates and constrain mode/axis. FTS5/BM25 should rank body text; semantic ranking should be optional, versioned, and only break lexical/structured ambiguity because the repository's semantic lane adds model/runtime dependencies while its hybrid API already supports separately switchable vector, FTS, BM25, graph, and trigger channels. The hub receives only candidate cards; hydration then preserves one coherent `DESIGN.md` plus provenance for interface, token-axis slices for foundations, motion sections only for motion, do/don't plus provenance for audit, and at most one calibration pair for md-generator. This keeps retrieval broad but context narrow and preserves each mode rather than flattening their logic. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:140-142,168-184,201-204] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122] [INFERENCE: synthesis of findings 1-5 and iteration-1 mode-consumption evidence]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n        \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-2-2-the-current-crawl-state-proves-why-a-hand-maintained-static-index-is-insufficien\",\n      \"text\": \"**The current crawl state proves why a hand-maintained static index is insufficient and why every published index needs freshness metadata.** The manual `styles/README.md` says 50 of 1,290 styles, while the read-only snapshot found 1,034 `DESIGN.md` bundles and the 1,290-row crawl manifest contained 1,034 `captured` plus 256 `pending` rows. The existing manifest is useful provenance/freshness input (`uuid`, URL, `lastmod`, slug, status, capture time, error), but it has no retrieval attributes, artifact hashes, token-axis statistics, or mode eligibility. This contradiction is resolved as manual-index staleness, not corpus uncertainty. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-12] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-18] [INFERENCE: read-only Python snapshot and manifest aggregation over `.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/` at 2026-07-18T09:40Z]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n        \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-2-1-the-strongest-repository-native-precedent-is-a-checked-source-manifest-plus-a-re\",\n      \"text\": \"**The strongest repository-native precedent is a checked source manifest plus a rebuildable query projection, not a database as source of truth.** The advisor's `leaf-manifest.json` is generated, must be byte-stable under `--check`, and authorizes exact routable paths; its SQLite graph separately indexes checked `graph-metadata.json`, records source paths and content hashes, and reports changed or missing sources by recomputing SHA-256. The styles harness already has the beginnings of the same split: committed `_manifest.json` is lastmod-keyed crawl state, while captured artifacts remain canonical. A styles retrieval manifest should therefore be committed and checkable, while any SQLite/FTS or embedding store should be disposable and generation-bound. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:87-99] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:23-28,37-49,91-96]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 2,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:80-114,285-313`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/README.md:115-154`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/mcp_server/handlers/skill-graph/status.ts:114-203`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/sqlite-fts.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:1-260`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/SKILL.md:130-214`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:13-112`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_manifest.json:1-24`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/README.md:1-61`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:136-367`\",\n        \"Read-only Python corpus, compact-manifest, file-scan, structured-query, and in-memory FTS5 benchmark output from the pinned 2026-07-18T09:40Z snapshot.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-3-2-bm25-materially-improved-the-two-discriminating-lexical-queries-while-determinis\",\n      \"text\": \"**BM25 materially improved the two discriminating lexical queries, while deterministic metadata remained useful for eligibility rather than final ranking.** Interface precision@5 rose from 0.20 to 0.80 and audit from 0.00 to 0.60; the five-query mean rose from 0.44 to 0.68. Foundations tied at 1.00 because 681 rows met a broad rubric, while md-generator tied at 1.00 because all 1,091 rows did, so those ties demonstrate structural eligibility but provide almost no ranking discrimination. This supports deterministic filters followed by lexical ranking, not BM25-only or metadata-only retrieval. [INFERENCE: top-5 results and rubric counts in the pinned ablation] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:20-26]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-4`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:11-102`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:8-140,375-480`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-3.md:6-53`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:14-95`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145`\",\n        \"Read-only in-memory snapshot, deterministic-rank, SQLite FTS5/BM25, candidate-card, and hydration-byte output for snapshot `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-3-4-candidate-discovery-can-stay-cheap-in-context-while-hydration-remains-mode-propo\",\n      \"text\": \"**Candidate discovery can stay cheap in context while hydration remains mode-proportional.** Five candidate cards cost 1,357–1,582 bytes per mode (7,302 bytes across all five queries). Selected hydration ranged from 845 bytes for motion fragments to 16,471 bytes for one md-generator calibration pair, with a 4,803-byte median and 40,088 bytes across five independently selected mode payloads. These measurements validate candidate-card-first delivery and show why full-document hydration belongs only to coherent-reference modes. [INFERENCE: UTF-8 byte measurement of serialized top-5 cards and selected payloads from the pinned snapshot] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115] [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-4`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:11-102`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:8-140,375-480`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-3.md:6-53`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:14-95`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145`\",\n        \"Read-only in-memory snapshot, deterministic-rank, SQLite FTS5/BM25, candidate-card, and hydration-byte output for snapshot `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-3-5-semantic-lift-remains-unmeasured-not-negative-repository-evidence-establishes-a-\",\n      \"text\": \"**Semantic lift remains unmeasured, not negative.** Repository evidence establishes a separately switchable semantic/vector lane, but this lineage has no verified corpus-specific labeled embedding index bound to the pinned generation. Running a different or newly built generation would break the controlled comparison, so no semantic result was fabricated. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145] [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:22-26] [INFERENCE: absence of a verified generation-bound semantic result in the lineage evidence]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-state.jsonl:1-4`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-strategy.md:11-102`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:8-140,375-480`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/prompts/iteration-3.md:6-53`\",\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/iterations/iteration-002.md:14-95`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-interface/SKILL.md:71-90`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-foundations/SKILL.md:55-103`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-motion/SKILL.md:51-66,97-113`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-audit/SKILL.md:23-29,95-115`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/sk-design/design-md-generator/SKILL.md:10-15,109-122`\",\n        \"`.opencode/skills/system-spec-kit/mcp_server/lib/search/hybrid-search.ts:4-18,99-145`\",\n        \"Read-only in-memory snapshot, deterministic-rank, SQLite FTS5/BM25, candidate-card, and hydration-byte output for snapshot `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`.\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"finding-3-1-the-comparison-used-a-stable-content-addressed-generation-rather-than-a-moving-d\",\n      \"text\": \"**The comparison used a stable, content-addressed generation rather than a moving directory count.** The snapshot contained 1,091 `DESIGN.md` documents and their 2,182 token/provenance siblings (3,273 files, 34,241,583 bytes); pre/post path, size, and mtime fingerprints matched, and the loaded bytes produced snapshot id `sha256:8b9b3d84696b0bbbb0aac6e67671f1c65ddc46b0fa23adf568e6a40ef6d04a39`. This removes the active-crawl ambiguity for this ablation without claiming that 1,091 is the final corpus size. [INFERENCE: read-only snapshot fingerprint and SHA-256 aggregation performed before ranking]\",\n      \"addedAtIteration\": 3,\n      \"sources\": [\n        \"`.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-config.json:1-75`\",","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":561,"totalLines":562,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json","time":{"start":1784371314829,"end":1784371314873}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07f247c42514d540016a5b58726a74819198d2043675716c5a"}},"id":"prt_f74d18075001DiooScXIwHycje","sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","messageID":"msg_f74d139cd001NFObtvGUjJPKQB"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784371314882,"sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_xg5xA08qNDEsjshYgqymNBYN","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-dashboard.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-dashboard.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: Deep Research Dashboard\n3: description: Auto-generated reducer view over the research packet.\n4: ---\n5: \n6: # Deep Research Dashboard - Session Overview\n7: \n8: Auto-generated from JSONL state log, iteration files, findings registry, and strategy state. Never manually edited.\n9: \n10: <!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n11: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n12: \n13: Reducer-generated observability surface for the active research packet.\n14: \n15: <!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n16: <!-- ANCHOR:status -->\n17: ## 2. STATUS\n18: - Topic: How should the sk-design skill and its five nested modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) smartly index, retrieve, and consume the ~1,290-style design-token library at .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/?\n19: - Started: 2026-07-18T09:27:16Z\n20: - Status: INITIALIZED\n21: - Iteration: 8 of 10\n22: - Session ID: fanout-sol-1784366607889-1j7alg\n23: - Parent Session: none\n24: - Lifecycle Mode: new\n25: - Generation: 1\n26: - continuedFromRun: none\n27: \n28: <!-- /ANCHOR:status -->\n29: <!-- ANCHOR:progress -->\n30: ## 3. PROGRESS\n31: \n32: | # | Focus | Track | Ratio | Findings | Status |\n33: |---|-------|-------|-------|----------|--------|\n34: | 1 | Inventory corpus shape, quantify representative token/document characteristics, and map artifacts to sk-design hub and mode contracts | corpus-architecture | 1.00 | 6 | complete |\n35: | 2 | Compare committed static indexing, a structured query store, on-demand DESIGN.md grep, and a layered hybrid using repository-native precedents and measured corpus costs | retrieval-architecture | 0.93 | 6 | complete |\n36: | 3 | Run a bounded mode-specific relevance and context-cost ablation for deterministic eligibility, BM25 top-5 ranking, and optional semantic evidence on one pinned corpus snapshot | retrieval-validation | 0.83 | 6 | complete |\n37: | 4 | Define and validate the hub-plus-five-mode consumption contract and deterministic one-coherent-reference versus bounded-synthesis procedure | mode-consumption | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n38: | 5 | Define and falsify an operational anti-slop proof gate for corpus use, including coherent-source fingerprinting, transformation deltas, trope limits, refusal paths, and audit integration | anti-slop-proof | 0.93 | 6 | complete |\n39: | 6 | Specify the minimal repository-native build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change lifecycle for sk-design style retrieval | tooling-lifecycle | 0.93 | 6 | complete |\n40: | 7 | Rank utilization strategies by leverage, build and operating cost, and provenance, license, staleness, size, and extraction-fidelity risk | strategy-risk-ranking | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n41: | 8 | Generation-bound human-auditable holdout and retrieval substrate closure | retrieval-validation | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n42: \n43: - iterationsCompleted: 8\n44: - keyFindings: 53\n45: - openQuestions: 0\n46: - resolvedQuestions: 5\n47: \n48: <!-- /ANCHOR:progress -->\n49: <!-- ANCHOR:questions -->\n50: ## 4. QUESTIONS\n51: - Answered: 5/5\n52: - [x] Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n53: - [x] What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n54: - [x] Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\n55: - [x] What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\n56: - [x] How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n57: \n58: <!-- /ANCHOR:questions -->\n59: <!-- ANCHOR:uncovered-questions -->\n60: ## Uncovered Questions\n61: - Count: 0\n62: - None\n63: \n64: <!-- /ANCHOR:uncovered-questions -->\n65: <!-- ANCHOR:trend -->\n66: ## 5. TREND\n67: - newInfoRatio sparkline: █▇▆▅▃▂▁▁▂▃▄▅▅▅▅▃▂▂▂▂\n68: - score sparkline: █▇▆▅▃▂▁▁▂▃▄▅▅▅▅▃▂▂▂▂\n69: - Last 3 ratios: 0.93 -> 0.85 -> 0.85\n70: - Stuck count: 0\n71: - Guard violations: none recorded by the reducer pass\n72: - convergenceScore: 0.85\n73: - coverageBySources: {\"code\":147,\"other\":18}\n74: - Advisory events: none\n75: \n76: <!-- /ANCHOR:trend -->\n77: <!-- ANCHOR:dead-ends -->\n78: ## 6. DEAD ENDS\n79: - **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric. (iteration 3)\n80: - Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot. (iteration 3)\n81: - Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker. (iteration 3)\n82: - Treating the five-query aggregate P@5 as a general corpus relevance score; the foundations and md-generator rubrics were too broad and the motion rubric had no positives. (iteration 3)\n83: - Using BM25 without deterministic mode/provenance/axis eligibility, even though BM25 outperformed metadata on the discriminating lexical queries. (iteration 3)\n84: - **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging. (iteration 4)\n85: - Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction. (iteration 4)\n86: - Treating incidental temporal words in a static style as motion evidence. (iteration 4)\n87: - Unbounded mixing of top-ranked styles or averaging token values. (iteration 4)\n88: - Using more than one study pair or any corpus synthesis in md-generator's measured phases. (iteration 4)\n89: - **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic. (iteration 5)\n90: - A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields. (iteration 5)\n91: - A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency. (iteration 5)\n92: - Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs. (iteration 5)\n93: - Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions. (iteration 5)\n94: - A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417] (iteration 6)\n95: - A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399] (iteration 6)\n96: - Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified. (iteration 6)\n97: - Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence. (iteration 6)\n98: - Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:98-106] (iteration 6)\n99: - Per-mode taste rules in the hub or engine: mode-supplied generic requirements preserve the hub's routing boundary. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:164-190,232-290] [INFERENCE: generic capabilities avoid central taste policy] (iteration 6)\n100: - Promote “watcher/daemon-based refresh for this corpus” to exhausted unless future profiling shows build/check latency above the interactive budget. (iteration 6)\n101: - Semantic embeddings in the first build: semantic lift is still unmeasured on a generation-bound labeled holdout. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:531-548] (iteration 6)\n102: - Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need. (iteration 7)\n103: - Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift. (iteration 7)\n104: - Promote default full-corpus prompt loading to an exhausted strategy: its apparent zero build cost hides maximum recurring context cost and bypasses candidate, provenance, hydration, and coherence controls. (iteration 7)\n105: - Shipping semantic reranking before a labeled, same-generation comparison: storage/versioning work cannot substitute for relevance evidence. (iteration 7)\n106: - Treating absent license fields as either permission or prohibition: the metadata supports only `unknown`, not a legal verdict. (iteration 7)\n107: - Treating the secondary scan's `malformed_urls` counter as corpus evidence: the URL regex consumed Markdown's `](` separator in duplicated link syntax; direct field coverage was retained, but that counter was discarded. (iteration 7)\n108: - BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction. (iteration 8)\n109: - Metadata-only final ranking; prior interface/audit evidence shows material lexical gains after deterministic eligibility. (iteration 8)\n110: - Promote “one ranker can be authoritative across all five modes” to exhausted; the evidence requires deterministic constraints, lexical ranking, and mode-owned judgment. (iteration 8)\n111: - Promote “semantic reranking required before baseline launch” to exhausted for this decision. Reconsider only as a separately measured same-generation ablation. (iteration 8)\n112: - Semantic reranking as a baseline dependency without a same-generation labeled comparison. (iteration 8)\n113: - Treating pooled recall as corpus-wide recall or this nine-candidate-per-mode pool as a universal gold standard. (iteration 8)\n114: \n115: <!-- /ANCHOR:dead-ends -->\n116: <!-- ANCHOR:divergent-pivots -->\n117: ## 6A. DIVERGENT PIVOTS\n118: - Completed pivots: 0\n119: - Failed pivots: 0\n120: - Audited overrides: 0\n121: - Saturated: none yet\n122: - Pivot lineage: none yet\n123: - Remaining frontier: none recorded\n124: \n125: <!-- /ANCHOR:divergent-pivots -->\n126: <!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n127: ## 7. NEXT FOCUS\n128: [All tracked questions are resolved]\n129: \n130: <!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n131: <!-- ANCHOR:active-risks -->\n132: ## 8. ACTIVE RISKS\n133: - None active beyond normal research uncertainty.\n134: \n135: <!-- /ANCHOR:active-risks -->\n136: <!-- ANCHOR:blocked-stops -->\n137: ## 9. BLOCKED STOPS\n138: No blocked-stop events recorded.\n139: \n140: <!-- /ANCHOR:blocked-stops -->\n141: <!-- ANCHOR:graph-convergence -->\n142: ## 10. GRAPH CONVERGENCE\n143: - graphConvergenceScore: 0.00\n144: - graphDecision: [Not recorded]\n145: - graphBlockers: none recorded\n146: \n147: <!-- /ANCHOR:graph-convergence -->\n\n(End of file - total 147 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: Deep Research Dashboard\ndescription: Auto-generated reducer view over the research packet.\n---\n\n# Deep Research Dashboard - Session Overview\n\nAuto-generated from JSONL state log, iteration files, findings registry, and strategy state. Never manually edited.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nReducer-generated observability surface for the active research packet.\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:status -->\n## 2. STATUS\n- Topic: How should the sk-design skill and its five nested modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) smartly index, retrieve, and consume the ~1,290-style design-token library at .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/?\n- Started: 2026-07-18T09:27:16Z\n- Status: INITIALIZED","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-dashboard.md","text":"---\ntitle: Deep Research Dashboard\ndescription: Auto-generated reducer view over the research packet.\n---\n\n# Deep Research Dashboard - Session Overview\n\nAuto-generated from JSONL state log, iteration files, findings registry, and strategy state. Never manually edited.\n\n<!-- ANCHOR:overview -->\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nReducer-generated observability surface for the active research packet.\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:overview -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:status -->\n## 2. STATUS\n- Topic: How should the sk-design skill and its five nested modes (interface, foundations, motion, audit, md-generator) smartly index, retrieve, and consume the ~1,290-style design-token library at .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/?\n- Started: 2026-07-18T09:27:16Z\n- Status: INITIALIZED\n- Iteration: 8 of 10\n- Session ID: fanout-sol-1784366607889-1j7alg\n- Parent Session: none\n- Lifecycle Mode: new\n- Generation: 1\n- continuedFromRun: none\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:status -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:progress -->\n## 3. PROGRESS\n\n| # | Focus | Track | Ratio | Findings | Status |\n|---|-------|-------|-------|----------|--------|\n| 1 | Inventory corpus shape, quantify representative token/document characteristics, and map artifacts to sk-design hub and mode contracts | corpus-architecture | 1.00 | 6 | complete |\n| 2 | Compare committed static indexing, a structured query store, on-demand DESIGN.md grep, and a layered hybrid using repository-native precedents and measured corpus costs | retrieval-architecture | 0.93 | 6 | complete |\n| 3 | Run a bounded mode-specific relevance and context-cost ablation for deterministic eligibility, BM25 top-5 ranking, and optional semantic evidence on one pinned corpus snapshot | retrieval-validation | 0.83 | 6 | complete |\n| 4 | Define and validate the hub-plus-five-mode consumption contract and deterministic one-coherent-reference versus bounded-synthesis procedure | mode-consumption | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n| 5 | Define and falsify an operational anti-slop proof gate for corpus use, including coherent-source fingerprinting, transformation deltas, trope limits, refusal paths, and audit integration | anti-slop-proof | 0.93 | 6 | complete |\n| 6 | Specify the minimal repository-native build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change lifecycle for sk-design style retrieval | tooling-lifecycle | 0.93 | 6 | complete |\n| 7 | Rank utilization strategies by leverage, build and operating cost, and provenance, license, staleness, size, and extraction-fidelity risk | strategy-risk-ranking | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n| 8 | Generation-bound human-auditable holdout and retrieval substrate closure | retrieval-validation | 0.85 | 6 | complete |\n\n- iterationsCompleted: 8\n- keyFindings: 53\n- openQuestions: 0\n- resolvedQuestions: 5\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:progress -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:questions -->\n## 4. QUESTIONS\n- Answered: 5/5\n- [x] Which retrieval substrate, or layered combination of substrates, best balances relevance, determinism, runtime cost, context size, and maintenance?\n- [x] What should the hub and each of the five modes consume, and when should a task reference one coherent real style versus synthesize selected attributes across several styles?\n- [x] Which anti-slop rules and proof gates keep outputs distinctive rather than averaging the corpus into a generic middle?\n- [x] What index build, query, refresh, validation, and corpus-change tooling is justified by the repository's existing patterns?\n- [x] How should utilization strategies rank by leverage versus build cost after accounting for size, staleness, licensing, provenance, and extraction fidelity risks?\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:questions -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:uncovered-questions -->\n## Uncovered Questions\n- Count: 0\n- None\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:uncovered-questions -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:trend -->\n## 5. TREND\n- newInfoRatio sparkline: █▇▆▅▃▂▁▁▂▃▄▅▅▅▅▃▂▂▂▂\n- score sparkline: █▇▆▅▃▂▁▁▂▃▄▅▅▅▅▃▂▂▂▂\n- Last 3 ratios: 0.93 -> 0.85 -> 0.85\n- Stuck count: 0\n- Guard violations: none recorded by the reducer pass\n- convergenceScore: 0.85\n- coverageBySources: {\"code\":147,\"other\":18}\n- Advisory events: none\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:trend -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:dead-ends -->\n## 6. DEAD ENDS\n- **Mechanical all-corpus substring labels as the final gold standard:** useful for a bounded smoke test, but zero- and near-universal-positive sets cannot validate ranking quality. Future evaluation should use a small human-labeled holdout with known positives and hard negatives rather than vary this same rubric. (iteration 3)\n- Claiming semantic improvement without a verified corpus-specific index and labels bound to the same snapshot. (iteration 3)\n- Interpreting the motion 0.00 scores as evidence against either ranker. (iteration 3)\n- Treating the five-query aggregate P@5 as a general corpus relevance score; the foundations and md-generator rubrics were too broad and the motion rubric had no positives. (iteration 3)\n- Using BM25 without deterministic mode/provenance/axis eligibility, even though BM25 outperformed metadata on the discriminating lexical queries. (iteration 3)\n- **Top-K-as-palette synthesis:** retrieving several relevant styles and blending their values cannot preserve provenance or a coherent design thesis. Candidate diversity is useful for selection or distinct alternatives, not averaging. (iteration 4)\n- Letting corpus rank override hub routing, user pins, target evidence, mode standards, or live measured extraction. (iteration 4)\n- Treating incidental temporal words in a static style as motion evidence. (iteration 4)\n- Unbounded mixing of top-ranked styles or averaging token values. (iteration 4)\n- Using more than one study pair or any corpus synthesis in md-generator's measured phases. (iteration 4)\n- **Similarity or novelty scoring as the anti-slop authority:** a visually unusual trope stack can score as novel while violating its named thesis. Use evidence rows and hard contradictions; similarity may only be diagnostic. (iteration 5)\n- A prose-only “be distinctive” reminder with no blocking evidence fields. (iteration 5)\n- A source citation alone as proof of coherence; content identity does not establish design consistency. (iteration 5)\n- Any numeric distinctiveness score that rewards adding more motifs. (iteration 5)\n- Audit choosing the design thesis or overruling interface/foundations/motion taste decisions. (iteration 5)\n- A committed SQLite/FTS database: it is larger than the compact manifest, environment-dependent, and fully derivable. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:401-417] (iteration 6)\n- A filesystem watcher or daemon: full bounded inventory is 51.09 ms and prior generation was 171.1 ms, so lifecycle complexity has no measured justification. [INFERENCE: current bounded inventory and prior benchmark in findings-registry.json:383-399] (iteration 6)\n- Do not retry “database as canonical state”; only a disposable generation-bound projection is justified. (iteration 6)\n- Keep “semantic ranking before a labeled, generation-bound evaluation” blocked; changing the storage wrapper does not resolve the missing evidence. (iteration 6)\n- Mandatory live Refero/browser tests in ordinary PR CI: the extractor already isolates that network-sensitive check behind `--self-test`. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/sk-design/styles/_harness/README.md:98-106] (iteration 6)\n- Per-mode taste rules in the hub or engine: mode-supplied generic requirements preserve the hub's routing boundary. [SOURCE: .opencode/skills/system-skill-advisor/SKILL.md:164-190,232-290] [INFERENCE: generic capabilities avoid central taste policy] (iteration 6)\n- Promote “watcher/daemon-based refresh for this corpus” to exhausted unless future profiling shows build/check latency above the interactive budget. (iteration 6)\n- Semantic embeddings in the first build: semantic lift is still unmeasured on a generation-bound labeled holdout. [SOURCE: .opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/findings-registry.json:531-548] (iteration 6)\n- Default full-document loading and watcher/service infrastructure: the former externalizes cost into context and copying exposure; the latter has no measured runtime need. (iteration 7)\n- Keep watcher/daemon/service retrieval and pre-evaluation semantic ranking blocked unless future measurements invalidate the current sub-second local lifecycle or demonstrate same-generation relevance lift. (iteration 7)\n- Promote default full-corpus prompt loading to an exhausted strategy: its apparent zero build cost hides maximum recurring context cost and bypasses candidate, provenance, hydration, and coherence controls. (iteration 7)\n- Shipping semantic reranking before a labeled, same-generation comparison: storage/versioning work cannot substitute for relevance evidence. (iteration 7)\n- Treating absent license fields as either permission or prohibition: the metadata supports only `unknown`, not a legal verdict. (iteration 7)\n- Treating the secondary scan's `malformed_urls` counter as corpus evidence: the URL regex consumed Markdown's `](` separator in duplicated link syntax; direct field coverage was retained, but that counter was discarded. (iteration 7)\n- BM25-only ranking for compositional or negated mode intents; high term frequency can reward an explicit contradiction. (iteration 8)\n- Metadata-only final ranking; prior interface/audit evidence shows material lexical gains after deterministic eligibility. (iteration 8)\n- Promote “one ranker can be authoritative across all five modes” to exhausted; the evidence requires deterministic constraints, lexical ranking, and mode-owned judgment. (iteration 8)\n- Promote “semantic reranking required before baseline launch” to exhausted for this decision. Reconsider only as a separately measured same-generation ablation. (iteration 8)\n- Semantic reranking as a baseline dependency without a same-generation labeled comparison. (iteration 8)\n- Treating pooled recall as corpus-wide recall or this nine-candidate-per-mode pool as a universal gold standard. (iteration 8)\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:dead-ends -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:divergent-pivots -->\n## 6A. DIVERGENT PIVOTS\n- Completed pivots: 0\n- Failed pivots: 0\n- Audited overrides: 0\n- Saturated: none yet\n- Pivot lineage: none yet\n- Remaining frontier: none recorded\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:divergent-pivots -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n## 7. NEXT FOCUS\n[All tracked questions are resolved]\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:next-focus -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:active-risks -->\n## 8. ACTIVE RISKS\n- None active beyond normal research uncertainty.\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:active-risks -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:blocked-stops -->\n## 9. BLOCKED STOPS\nNo blocked-stop events recorded.\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:blocked-stops -->\n<!-- ANCHOR:graph-convergence -->\n## 10. GRAPH CONVERGENCE\n- graphConvergenceScore: 0.00\n- graphDecision: [Not recorded]\n- graphBlockers: none recorded\n\n<!-- /ANCHOR:graph-convergence -->","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":147,"totalLines":147,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/sk-design/011-sk-design-styles-utilization/001-research-utilization/research/lineages/sol/deep-research-dashboard.md","time":{"start":1784371314859,"end":1784371314881}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07f247c42514d540016a5b58726a7c8191b6f69b096767cff4"}},"id":"prt_f74d180a1001JQETeqMs3XMYCP","sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","messageID":"msg_f74d139cd001NFObtvGUjJPKQB"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784371314927,"sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ukjNYtxSDwwS0yb81bx33OPU","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\n3: description: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"opencode cli reference\"\n6:   - \"opencode run flags\"\n7:   - \"opencode model selection\"\n8:   - \"opencode provider auth pre-flight\"\n9:   - \"opencode variant reasoning effort\"\n10:   - \"opencode version drift\"\n11: importance_tier: important\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 1.3.0.29\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n17: \n18: Comprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: ### Core Principle\n25: \n26: OpenCode is the framework that owns this repository. The same binary that hosts the operator's TUI session also accepts non-interactive invocations through `opencode run`. The cli-opencode skill calls `opencode run` from external runtimes (Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell) so the calling AI can dispatch a task into a fresh OpenCode session that loads the full plugin, skill, MCP, and Spec Kit Memory runtime.\n27: \n28: ### Purpose\n29: \n30: Provide a single-source reference for the OpenCode CLI surface — every subcommand cli-opencode invokes, every flag it pins, every agent it can route to, the version baseline it is built against, and the error envelopes that need explicit recovery.\n31: \n32: ### When to Use\n33: \n34: - Looking up an OpenCode CLI subcommand or flag during a delegation\n35: - Selecting a model + variant + agent for a dispatch\n36: - Confirming the version baseline before pinning a flag set\n37: - Troubleshooting a failed `opencode run` invocation\n38: - Confirming the self-invocation guard signal against the live binary\n39: \n40: ### Key Sources\n41: \n42: | Source | URL |\n43: |--------|-----|\n44: | **Binary** | `$(command -v opencode)` (typically `~/.superset/bin/opencode` or another local bin path) |\n45: | **Repository** | https://github.com/sst/opencode |\n46: | **Version baseline** | v1.3.17 (pinned in this reference) |\n47: | **Runtime** | Node.js 18+ for the npm install path; standalone binary on macOS |\n48: \n49: ---\n50: \n51: ## 2. INSTALLATION\n52: \n53: | Method | Command | Notes |\n54: |--------|---------|-------|\n55: | **Standalone** | `curl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install \\| bash` | macOS / Linux installer |\n56: | **Homebrew** | `brew install opencode` | macOS package manager |\n57: | **npm global** | `npm install -g opencode-ai` | Cross-platform when Node.js 18+ is present |\n58: | **Upgrade** | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Pin a specific version with the `target` argument |\n59: | **Uninstall** | `opencode uninstall` | Removes the binary and related state |\n60: \n61: After installation, run `opencode --version` to confirm. The cli-opencode skill is pinned to v1.3.17. Newer binaries may add or rename flags — consult Section 9 (Version Drift) before relying on a non-pinned flag.\n62: \n63: ---\n64: \n65: ## 3. SUBCOMMAND MAP\n66: \n67: OpenCode exposes a multi-subcommand surface. The cli-opencode skill primarily invokes `run`, with secondary use of `serve`, `web`, `agent`, and `debug`.\n68: \n69: | Subcommand | Purpose | Invoked by cli-opencode |\n70: |------------|---------|-------------------------|\n71: | `opencode` (default) | Start the TUI in the current project | No (interactive only) |\n72: | `opencode run [message..]` | Non-interactive single-shot dispatch | YES (canonical use case) |\n73: | `opencode serve` | Start a headless server | YES (for parallel detached sessions) |\n74: | `opencode web` | Start a server plus open the web interface | YES (when the operator wants a browser surface) |\n75: | `opencode acp` | Start an ACP (Agent Client Protocol) server | No (specialized integration path) |\n76: | `opencode attach <url>` | Attach to a running OpenCode server | YES (for share-URL flows) |\n77: | `opencode agent` | Manage agent definitions | YES (for agent listing) |\n78: | `opencode debug` | Debugging and troubleshooting tools | YES (for `debug skill` and `debug agent` listings) |\n79: | `opencode mcp` | Manage MCP server registrations | No |\n80: | `opencode providers` (alias `auth`) | Manage AI providers and credentials | No (operator-driven setup) |\n81: | `opencode models [provider]` | List available models | YES (for capability discovery) |\n82: | `opencode session` | Manage sessions | No (state inspection only) |\n83: | `opencode export [sessionID]` | Export session data as JSON | YES (for memory handback flows) |\n84: | `opencode stats` | Token and cost statistics | No |\n85: | `opencode db` | Database tools | No |\n86: | `opencode plugin <module>` (alias `plug`) | Install a plugin | No (operator-driven setup) |\n87: | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Upgrade the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n88: | `opencode uninstall` | Uninstall the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 4. `opencode run` FLAGS\n93: \n94: `opencode run [message..]` is the canonical non-interactive entry point. The cli-opencode skill builds every dispatch around this subcommand.\n95: \n96: ### Core flags\n97: \n98: | Flag / Option | Type | Purpose |\n99: |---------------|------|---------|\n100: | `[message..]` | positional | One or more positional message strings |\n101: | `--print-logs` | boolean | Stream logs to stderr |\n102: | `--log-level` | enum | `DEBUG`, `INFO`, `WARN`, `ERROR` |\n103: | `--pure` | boolean | Run without external plugins (skill loads disabled) |\n104: | `--command` | string | Run a known command, the message becomes its args |\n105: | `-c`, `--continue` | boolean | Continue the last session in this project |\n106: | `-s`, `--session` | string | Continue a specific session id |\n107: | `--fork` | boolean | Fork before continuing — requires `--continue` or `--session` |\n108: | `--share` | boolean | Publish a shareable URL for this session |\n109: | `-m`, `--model` | string | Provider/model selector — e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` |\n110: | `--agent` | string | Agent slug (loads from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md`) |\n111: | `--format` | enum | `default` (formatted) or `json` (raw event stream) |\n112: | `-f`, `--file` | array | Attach files to the message |\n113: | `--title` | string | Session title (truncated message used when omitted) |\n114: | `--attach` | string | Attach to a running OpenCode server URL |\n115: | `-p`, `--password` | string | Basic auth password (or `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD`) |\n116: | `--dir` | string | Working directory or remote-server path |\n117: | `--port` | number | Local server port (random when omitted) |\n118: | `--variant` | string | Provider-specific reasoning effort (`high`, `max`, `minimal`, etc.) |\n119: | `--thinking` | boolean | Show thinking blocks (default false) |\n120: \n121: > **`--command` semantics (verified on v1.17.4):** the `run` message is plain text — slash-command syntax inside it (`opencode run \"/memory:search query\"`) is NOT expanded, so the command's template never reaches the model. Executing a registered command non-interactively requires `--command <family>/<name>` with the args as the message (they become `$ARGUMENTS`). Registry names are slash-namespaced (`memory/search` for `/memory:search`); a wrong name fails with the full registry list. Behavior probes of slash commands MUST use `--command`; the raw-text form only measures the model freestyling without the contract. Consequences: (a) any behavior/adherence probe of a slash command MUST use `--command`, and the raw-text form is only valid as a labeled negative control; (b) inside `` !`…` `` template injections `$ARGUMENTS` expands like `\"$@\"` — one word per argument — so renderer scripts must join argv themselves.\n122: \n123: ### cli-opencode default invocation shape\n124: \n125: The skill builds every dispatch from a base shape and overlays use-case-specific flags:\n126: \n127: ```bash\n128: opencode run \\\n129:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n130:   --agent <agent-slug> \\\n131:   --variant high \\\n132:   --format json \\\n133:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n134:   \"<prompt>\"\n135: ```\n136: \n137: | Flag | Default | Reason |\n138: |------|---------|--------|\n139: | `--model` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Direct DeepSeek is the default provider — elevated reasoning at low cost; operator may override (e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash`, `kimi-for-coding/k2p7`, or any live OpenAI GPT-5.6 slug: `openai/gpt-5.6`, `openai/gpt-5.6-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) |\n140: | `--agent` | per use case | Required for use case 1 / 3; optional for use case 2 |\n141: | `--variant high` | high | Routine cli-opencode dispatches benefit from elevated reasoning effort |\n142: | `--format json` | json | Structured event stream is what external runtimes parse |\n143: | `--dir` | repo root | Pin the working directory to avoid CWD ambiguity |\n144: \n145: ### Stdin handling — `</dev/null` is required for non-interactive dispatch\n146: \n147: > **opencode v1.14.39 reads stdin at startup before session creation.** If you redirect stdout/stderr to files in automation (`> stdout.log 2> stderr.log`), opencode hangs at 0% CPU after the `+60s snapshot prune cleanup` log line because stdin remains attached to the parent terminal and never receives EOF.\n148: \n149: ALWAYS append `</dev/null` AFTER the prompt argument and BEFORE the stdout/stderr redirects:\n150: \n151: ```bash\n152: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n153: #                                  ^^^^^^^^^^\n154: #                                  redirects stdin from /dev/null → immediate EOF\n155: ```\n156: \n157: Foreground `| tail` accidentally works because the upstream pipe stage provides closed stdin, but `> file 2> file` does not. See `references/integration_patterns.md` §6 for the full failure-mode + fix matrix and `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 for the discovery context.\n158: \n159: ### Sessions, share URLs, and ports\n160: \n161: `--share` publishes the session over the OpenCode share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). External-runtime dispatches do NOT publish share URLs by default.\n162: \n163: `--port` only matters when the dispatch needs to bind a known port (e.g. for a parallel detached session that another tool will attach to). The default random port is correct for one-shot dispatches.\n164: \n165: `--continue` and `--session <id>` reuse prior session state. `--fork` branches an existing session into a new one. cli-opencode uses session continuation in memory handback flows where the calling AI wants to thread context across multiple delegations.\n166: \n167: ### Provider Auth Pre-Flight (smart fallback)\n168: \n169: Before the first dispatch in a session, run a one-shot auth pre-flight against `opencode providers list` so a missing default doesn't fail mid-dispatch. Cache the result for the session; only re-run on auth failure.\n170: \n171: ```bash\n172: # Pre-flight — one call per session\n173: PROVIDERS=$(opencode providers list 2>&1)\n174: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"deepseek\"            && DEEPSEEK_OK=1       || DEEPSEEK_OK=0\n175: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"minimax-coding-plan\" && MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1  || MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0   # MiniMax Token Plan (default MiniMax path)\n176: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"minimax([^-]|$)\"    && MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1 || MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0  # MiniMax Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the coding-plan provider\n177: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"xiaomi-token-plan-ams\" && XIAOMI_OK=1       || XIAOMI_OK=0          # Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\n178: echo \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"xiaomi([^-]|$)\"     && XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1 || XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0   # Xiaomi Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the token-plan-ams provider\n179: echo \"default=$DEEPSEEK_OK minimax_token=$MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK minimax_direct=$MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK xiaomi=$XIAOMI_OK xiaomi_direct=$XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK\"\n180: ```\n181: \n182: | State | DEEPSEEK_OK | Action |\n183: |-------|-------------|--------|\n184: | Default available | 1 | Proceed with `--model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --variant high` |\n185: | Default missing | 0 | **ASK user** before substituting (offer A: openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro, B: login deepseek and retry, C: name a different model) — do not dispatch until configured |\n186: \n187: **MiniMax routing** (default = Token Plan; Direct API is the pay-per-token alternative):\n188: \n189: | State | Condition | Action |\n190: |-------|-----------|--------|\n191: | MiniMax requested (default) | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` — **omit `--agent`** (rejected on opencode 1.15.13) |\n192: | Token Plan not configured | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → MiniMax Token Plan — never substitute silently |\n193: | Direct API explicitly requested | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax/MiniMax-M3` (pay-per-token; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax`) |\n194: | Direct API requested, not configured | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to configure the `minimax` provider (`MINIMAX_API_KEY`) — do not substitute silently |\n195: \n196: **MiMo routing** (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe and Xiaomi Direct API; explicitly-selectable — first match wins):\n197: \n198: | State | Condition | Action |\n199: |-------|-----------|--------|\n200: | MiMo requested (default) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` — **omit `--agent`** (`--agent general` warns and falls back on opencode 1.15.13). Confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n201: | MiMo speed variant (\"ultraspeed\", latency-sensitive) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` — low-latency MiMo-V2.5-Pro tier, same prompt contract |\n202: | Token Plan explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_OK=1` | `--model xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` — NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead |\n203: | Token Plan not configured | `XIAOMI_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — never substitute silently |\n204: | Direct API explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` or `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` (pay-per-token; confirm live ids via `opencode models xiaomi`) |\n205: | Direct API requested, not configured | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode providers login xiaomi` — never substitute silently |\n206: \n207: **Login / setup command shapes** (the AI surfaces these to the user; the user runs them in their own terminal):\n208: \n209: ```bash\n210: # Recommended default — direct DeepSeek API\n211: opencode providers login deepseek\n212: \n213: # MiniMax Token Plan — DEFAULT MiniMax path (subscription). Interactive: pick \"MiniMax Token Plan (minimax.io)\".\n214: opencode auth login          # → provider minimax-coding-plan; Anthropic-compatible https://api.minimax.io/anthropic/v1 (China: api.minimaxi.com)\n215: \n216: # MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative (needs MINIMAX_API_KEY; platform endpoint https://api.minimax.io/v1)\n217: opencode providers login minimax\n218: \n219: # Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — provider-managed endpoint. Interactive: pick \"Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\".\n220: opencode auth login          # → provider xiaomi-token-plan-ams (Xiaomi Token Plan, Europe)\n221: \n222: # Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token alternative\n223: opencode providers login xiaomi\n224: \n225: # Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM coding subscription. Interactive: pick \"Z.AI Coding Plan\".\n226: opencode auth login          # → provider zai-coding-plan; model zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2\n227: ```\n228: \n229: > Do not mix region endpoints (international `minimax.io` vs China `minimaxi.com`). Confirm live model ids with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan`. The Xiaomi endpoint is provider-managed (no documented base URL — do not invent one); confirm live model ids with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Token Plan) or `opencode models xiaomi` (Direct API).\n230: \n231: **On auth-error mid-dispatch** (`401 Unauthorized`, `provider/model not found`): invalidate the cache, rerun the pre-flight, and apply the same decision tree before retrying. Never substitute a model the user didn't approve.\n232: \n233: ### User-facing prompt templates\n234: \n235: Surface these verbatim to the operator when the pre-flight decision tree lands on \"ASK user\" (default missing with a fallback configured, or all providers missing). Never dispatch until the operator responds.\n236: \n237: **Default missing, fallback configured:**\n238: \n239: ```text\n240: The skill default `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` is not configured on this machine.\n241: A configured fallback is available. Pick one:\n242:   A) Use `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro --variant high` (OpenAI premium, configured now — paid)\n243:   B) Use `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro --variant high` (Xiaomi Direct API, configured now) — or `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed --variant high` for latency-sensitive runs\n244:   C) Use `kimi-for-coding/k2p7` (Kimi For Coding plan, configured now — subscription)\n245:   D) Run `opencode providers login deepseek` first, then retry the original dispatch\n246:   E) Name a different model — paste the `--model <provider/model>` you want to use\n247: ```\n248: \n249: **All providers missing:**\n250: \n251: ```text\n252: No supported providers are configured on this machine. Run one:\n253:   - `opencode providers login deepseek`     (recommended — default for cli-opencode)\n254:   - `opencode auth login`                   (MiniMax Token Plan — default MiniMax path; pick \"MiniMax Token Plan (minimax.io)\" → provider minimax-coding-plan; model minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3)\n255:   - `opencode providers login minimax`      (MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token; needs MINIMAX_API_KEY; model minimax/MiniMax-M3)\n256:   - `opencode auth login`                   (Xiaomi Token Plan — default Xiaomi path; pick \"Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\" → provider xiaomi-token-plan-ams; model xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro)\n257:   - `opencode providers login xiaomi`       (Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token; models xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro and xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed)\n258:   - `opencode auth login`                   (Kimi For Coding plan — Kimi/Moonshot coding subscription; provider kimi-for-coding; model kimi-for-coding/k2p7)\n259:   - `opencode auth login`                   (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM coding subscription; provider zai-coding-plan; model zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2)\n260:   - `opencode providers login openai`       (OpenAI premium alternative — paid)\n261: Which would you like to set up? Confirm when login finishes; the skill will retry the original dispatch.\n262: ```\n263: \n264: **Error-recovery contract.** If a dispatch returns an auth error after pre-flight passed (credential expired or rotated), invalidate the cache, rerun the pre-flight, and apply the same decision tree before retrying. Never substitute a model the user didn't approve.\n265: \n266: ---\n267: \n268: ## 5. MODEL SELECTION\n269: \n270: OpenCode resolves models through configured providers. The cli-opencode skill supports `deepseek` (default), `minimax-coding-plan` (MiniMax Token Plan — default MiniMax path), `minimax` (MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative), `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe — MiMo, explicitly-selectable; NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead), and `xiaomi` (Xiaomi Direct API — MiMo: `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` + low-latency `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, pay-per-token) — confirmed against `opencode providers list` and `opencode models`. Run `opencode models [provider]` for the full live list on a given install.\n271: \n272: | Provider | Example model id | Use case |\n273: |----------|------------------|----------|\n274: | `deepseek` (DEFAULT) | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Default — deep reasoning at low cost via direct DeepSeek API |\n275: | `deepseek` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash` | Latency-optimized direct-API sibling |\n276: | `kimi-for-coding` | `kimi-for-coding/k2p7` | Long-context Kimi K2.7 Code (256k; subscription plan) |\n277: | `zai-coding-plan` | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2` | Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM-5.2 flagship long-horizon coding (1M context; subscription); omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models zai-coding-plan` |\n278: | `minimax-coding-plan` (DEFAULT MiniMax) | `minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Token Plan (subscription) — default MiniMax dispatch; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan` |\n279: | `minimax` | `minimax/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative; needs `MINIMAX_API_KEY`; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax` |\n280: | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — MiMo-V2.5-Pro: 1M-token context, strongly agentic (1000+ tool calls), token-efficient; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` |\n281: | `xiaomi` | `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token; MiMo-V2.5-Pro; confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n282: \n283: `opencode models <provider>` lists every model id the provider exposes. The model string passed to `--model` is always `provider/model-id`.\n284: \n285: ### Reasoning effort via `--variant`\n286: \n287: The `--variant` flag maps to provider-specific reasoning effort. Underlying-model conventions apply per provider routing.\n288: \n289: | Provider | Variant values |\n290: |----------|----------------|\n291: | `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-pro`) | reasoning effort accepted |\n292: | `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-flash`) | non-reasoning — `--variant` ignored |\n293: | `minimax-coding-plan` / `minimax` (MiniMax-M3) | `--variant` behavior unverified — omitted by default; confirm against the MiniMax API before relying on it |\n294: | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (mimo-v2.5-pro) | `--variant` maps to MiMo reasoning effort (low/medium/high); **always use `--variant high`** (confirmed accepted on opencode 1.15.13) |\n295: | `zai-coding-plan` (glm-5.2) | GLM has native `reasoning_effort` (high/max); whether opencode `--variant` forwards to it is unverified — smoke-test before relying on it |\n296: | `openai` GPT-5.6 (`gpt-5.6` / `gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) | `--variant` maps to OpenAI reasoning effort — a separate lever from the model tier: `none`/`low`/`medium`/`high`/**`xhigh`** (Pro tiers — `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`: `medium`/`high`/`xhigh` — **inferred from the now-retired `gpt-5.5-pro` mapping and unverified against the live catalog (which no longer lists `gpt-5.5-pro` to re-check); smoke-test a Pro slug at `--variant low` before relying on the restriction**). **The `-fast` slugs** (`gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast`) are the low-latency **Fast** model tier (OpenAI `priority` service tier) with the same effort range — e.g. `--model openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast --variant xhigh`. `gpt-5.6-sol` is the flagship default; confirm live slugs via `opencode models openai`. |\n297: \n298: Default skill behavior: pass `--variant high` for cross-AI dispatches. Operators may override via the prompt template's variant field.\n299: \n300: ### Model-specific operational caveats\n301: \n302: - **Kimi K2.7 Code (`kimi-for-coding/k2p7`) over-exploration (observed 2026-06-17):** on broad / large-repo scopes at `--variant high`, k2p7 over-explores (many sequential reads) and can exceed a 600s timeout WITHOUT emitting — opencode flushes only the final assistant message to stdout, so a killed run yields 0 bytes (looks like a hang, but it was working). Mitigate with a hard read-cap in the prompt (\"read ≤N files then emit\") + a 1200s+ timeout, or omit `--variant`.\n303: - **GLM-5.2 (`zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`) latency variance (benchmark 008, n=45):** thinking-on drives latency variance 6–161s (avg ~26s) — budget generous timeouts; expect ~1/45 transient dispatch failures (retry the cell). Empirical prompt framework: COSTAR (benchmark 008).\n304: - **GLM-5.2 vision (image input):** `glm-5.2` is natively multimodal (vision-to-code), but `opencode run --file <image>` does NOT deliver images to this provider — upstream #20802 for custom OpenAI-compatible providers (confirmed 2026-06-28: `--file` → `NO_IMAGE_RECEIVED`). For image input use the direct Z.AI Coding Plan multimodal API (base64 `image_url` at `https://api.z.ai/api/coding/paas/v4/chat/completions`) — a deviation from this skill's dispatch path justified only by the verified #20802 breakage; see `../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md` §7.\n305: \n306: ---\n307: \n308: ## 6. AGENT FLAG\n309: \n310: `--agent <slug>` loads an agent definition from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md` (project-local) or the user-level fallback. The agent definition's frontmatter pins the model, tool permissions, and system prompt that shape the dispatch.\n311: \n312: ### Discovering agents\n313: \n314: | Command | What it shows |\n315: |---------|---------------|\n316: | `opencode agent list` | All registered agent slugs across project + user scopes |\n317: | `opencode debug agent <slug>` | Resolved frontmatter and system prompt for a slug |\n318: | `opencode debug skill <slug>` | Skill resolution for a slug if the agent loads one |\n319: \n320: ### Agent slugs in this repo\n321: \n322: | Slug | Role |\n323: |------|------|\n324: | `general` | Implementation, default subagent |\n325: | `context` | Read-only retrieval and search |\n326: | `orchestrate` | Multi-agent coordination |\n327: | `write` | Documentation generation |\n328: | `review` | Code review and PR analysis |\n329: | `debug` | Fresh-perspective debugging |\n330: | `deep-research` | Iterative research loop executor |\n331: | `deep-review` | Iterative code review loop executor |\n332: | `ai-council` | Multi-strategy planning |\n333: | `deep-improvement` | Agent improvement proposal mutator |\n334: \n335: The cli-opencode skill defers to the calling AI on agent selection — see `references/agent_delegation.md` for the routing matrix and `assets/prompt_templates.md` for canonical invocation shapes.\n336: \n337: ---\n338: \n339: ## 7. OUTPUT FORMAT AND EVENT STREAM\n340: \n341: `--format default` produces a human-formatted log. `--format json` emits a newline-delimited JSON event stream.\n342: \n343: ### JSON event shape (v1.3.17)\n344: \n345: Each line is a JSON object with at minimum:\n346: \n347: | Field | Meaning |\n348: |-------|---------|\n349: | `type` | Event type (`session.started`, `message.delta`, `tool.call`, `tool.result`, `session.completed`, ...) |\n350: | `timestamp` | ISO 8601 UTC timestamp |\n351: | `session_id` | The session id assigned by OpenCode |\n352: | `payload` | Type-specific payload |\n353: \n354: External runtimes parse the stream incrementally to surface tool calls, partial messages, and the final summary. cli-opencode prompt templates always pass `--format json` so the calling AI parses structured events instead of guessing format boundaries.\n355: \n356: ---\n357: \n358: ## 8. STATE LOCATION AND SHARE URLS\n359: \n360: ### State directory\n361: \n362: OpenCode persists session state in a shared SQLite database and storage tree under `~/.local/share/opencode/`:\n363: \n364: - `opencode.db` (`-shm`/`-wal` companions) — the session/message database\n365: - `storage/` — per-session structured artifacts\n366: - `snapshot/` — working-tree snapshots\n367: \n368: There is no per-session directory under `~/.opencode/state/<session_id>/` on a standard install — that path does not exist on this runtime layout. To inspect a specific session, use `opencode export <session_id>` (§3) rather than reading files from a state directory. The cli-opencode self-invocation guard's Layer 3 lock-file probe (`~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock`, per ADR-001) targets the older path as a best-effort third layer on top of the env-var and process-ancestry checks; treat it as a heuristic, not a verified-present artifact, on installs where `~/.opencode/state/` does not exist.\n369: \n370: ### Share URLs\n371: \n372: `--share` publishes a session URL via OpenCode's share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). The CHK-033 P1 checklist item requires operator confirmation before publishing a share URL because the URL exposes the session contents.\n373: \n374: ---\n375: \n376: ## 9. VERSION DRIFT\n377: \n378: This reference is pinned to OpenCode v1.3.17. If the live binary reports a different version, do the following:\n379: \n380: 1. Run `opencode run --help` and diff the flag list against Section 4.\n381: 2. Run `opencode --help` and diff the subcommand list against Section 3.\n382: 3. If a flag was renamed, prefer the new name in the dispatch. If a flag was removed, fall back to the closest analogue and surface the drift in the calling AI's response.\n383: 4. If the operator's machine has a major version bump (v1.4+, v2.x), re-validate the entire skill against the new flag table and bump the cli-opencode minor version.\n384: \n385: ### Failure modes specific to drift\n386: \n387: | Symptom | Likely cause |\n388: |---------|--------------|\n389: | `unknown option --variant` | v1.2 or earlier — variant flag was named `--reasoning` |\n390: | `unknown option --share` | Older standalone build without share infrastructure |\n391: | `unknown option --format json` | v1.0 — JSON event stream was the default and the flag did not exist |\n392: | `MODULE_NOT_FOUND` | Plugin loader crash; rerun with `--pure` to bypass plugins |\n393: \n394: ---\n395: \n396: ## 10. TROUBLESHOOTING\n397: \n398: | Symptom | Cause | Fix |\n399: |---------|-------|-----|\n400: | `command not found: opencode` | Binary not on PATH | Install via standalone installer or `brew install opencode` |\n401: | `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD required` | Server enforces basic auth | Pass `-p <password>` or set the env var |\n402: | `provider/model not found` | Provider not configured | Run `opencode providers` to enumerate, then `auth login <provider>` |\n403: | Empty output stream | `--format default` with non-TTY parent | Pass `--format json` and parse the event stream |\n404: | Session never finishes | Tool call hung | Run `opencode export <session_id>` and inspect the message log it returns |\n405: | Plugin load crash | Misconfigured plugin | Rerun with `--pure` to bypass all plugins |\n406: | Self-invocation refused | cli-opencode detected an in-OpenCode runtime | Use a sibling cli-* skill or a fresh shell session — see ADR-001 |\n407: | `--share` URL leaks | Share infrastructure published a session containing secrets | Operator MUST confirm before publishing per CHK-033 |\n408: \n409: ---\n410: \n411: ## 11. RELATED RESOURCES\n412: \n413: - `./integration_patterns.md` - The three documented use cases and their copy-paste invocation shapes\n414: - `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix and invocation patterns\n415: - `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique capabilities (full plugin/skill/MCP runtime, parallel detached sessions)\n416: - `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste prompt templates per use case\n417: - `../assets/prompt_quality_card.md` - Framework selection and CLEAR 5-check\n418: - `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router\n\n(End of file - total 418 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\ndescription: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode cli reference\"\n  - \"opencode run flags\"\n  - \"opencode model selection\"\n  - \"opencode provider auth pre-flight\"\n  - \"opencode variant reasoning effort\"\n  - \"opencode version drift\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.29\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n\nComprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\"\ndescription: \"Comprehensive reference for OpenCode CLI subcommands, flags, models, configuration, agent flags, sandbox boundaries, and troubleshooting. Pinned to v1.3.17.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode cli reference\"\n  - \"opencode run flags\"\n  - \"opencode model selection\"\n  - \"opencode provider auth pre-flight\"\n  - \"opencode variant reasoning effort\"\n  - \"opencode version drift\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.29\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Complete Command Reference\n\nComprehensive reference for the OpenCode CLI binary, every subcommand the cli-opencode skill dispatches against, the flag set it relies on, the agent surface it can target, and the failure modes that need explicit handling. Pinned to v1.3.17 baseline.\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Core Principle\n\nOpenCode is the framework that owns this repository. The same binary that hosts the operator's TUI session also accepts non-interactive invocations through `opencode run`. The cli-opencode skill calls `opencode run` from external runtimes (Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell) so the calling AI can dispatch a task into a fresh OpenCode session that loads the full plugin, skill, MCP, and Spec Kit Memory runtime.\n\n### Purpose\n\nProvide a single-source reference for the OpenCode CLI surface — every subcommand cli-opencode invokes, every flag it pins, every agent it can route to, the version baseline it is built against, and the error envelopes that need explicit recovery.\n\n### When to Use\n\n- Looking up an OpenCode CLI subcommand or flag during a delegation\n- Selecting a model + variant + agent for a dispatch\n- Confirming the version baseline before pinning a flag set\n- Troubleshooting a failed `opencode run` invocation\n- Confirming the self-invocation guard signal against the live binary\n\n### Key Sources\n\n| Source | URL |\n|--------|-----|\n| **Binary** | `$(command -v opencode)` (typically `~/.superset/bin/opencode` or another local bin path) |\n| **Repository** | https://github.com/sst/opencode |\n| **Version baseline** | v1.3.17 (pinned in this reference) |\n| **Runtime** | Node.js 18+ for the npm install path; standalone binary on macOS |\n\n---\n\n## 2. INSTALLATION\n\n| Method | Command | Notes |\n|--------|---------|-------|\n| **Standalone** | `curl -fsSL https://opencode.ai/install \\| bash` | macOS / Linux installer |\n| **Homebrew** | `brew install opencode` | macOS package manager |\n| **npm global** | `npm install -g opencode-ai` | Cross-platform when Node.js 18+ is present |\n| **Upgrade** | `opencode upgrade [target]` | Pin a specific version with the `target` argument |\n| **Uninstall** | `opencode uninstall` | Removes the binary and related state |\n\nAfter installation, run `opencode --version` to confirm. The cli-opencode skill is pinned to v1.3.17. Newer binaries may add or rename flags — consult Section 9 (Version Drift) before relying on a non-pinned flag.\n\n---\n\n## 3. SUBCOMMAND MAP\n\nOpenCode exposes a multi-subcommand surface. The cli-opencode skill primarily invokes `run`, with secondary use of `serve`, `web`, `agent`, and `debug`.\n\n| Subcommand | Purpose | Invoked by cli-opencode |\n|------------|---------|-------------------------|\n| `opencode` (default) | Start the TUI in the current project | No (interactive only) |\n| `opencode run [message..]` | Non-interactive single-shot dispatch | YES (canonical use case) |\n| `opencode serve` | Start a headless server | YES (for parallel detached sessions) |\n| `opencode web` | Start a server plus open the web interface | YES (when the operator wants a browser surface) |\n| `opencode acp` | Start an ACP (Agent Client Protocol) server | No (specialized integration path) |\n| `opencode attach <url>` | Attach to a running OpenCode server | YES (for share-URL flows) |\n| `opencode agent` | Manage agent definitions | YES (for agent listing) |\n| `opencode debug` | Debugging and troubleshooting tools | YES (for `debug skill` and `debug agent` listings) |\n| `opencode mcp` | Manage MCP server registrations | No |\n| `opencode providers` (alias `auth`) | Manage AI providers and credentials | No (operator-driven setup) |\n| `opencode models [provider]` | List available models | YES (for capability discovery) |\n| `opencode session` | Manage sessions | No (state inspection only) |\n| `opencode export [sessionID]` | Export session data as JSON | YES (for memory handback flows) |\n| `opencode stats` | Token and cost statistics | No |\n| `opencode db` | Database tools | No |\n| `opencode plugin <module>` (alias `plug`) | Install a plugin | No (operator-driven setup) |\n| `opencode upgrade [target]` | Upgrade the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n| `opencode uninstall` | Uninstall the binary | No (operator-driven) |\n\n---\n\n## 4. `opencode run` FLAGS\n\n`opencode run [message..]` is the canonical non-interactive entry point. The cli-opencode skill builds every dispatch around this subcommand.\n\n### Core flags\n\n| Flag / Option | Type | Purpose |\n|---------------|------|---------|\n| `[message..]` | positional | One or more positional message strings |\n| `--print-logs` | boolean | Stream logs to stderr |\n| `--log-level` | enum | `DEBUG`, `INFO`, `WARN`, `ERROR` |\n| `--pure` | boolean | Run without external plugins (skill loads disabled) |\n| `--command` | string | Run a known command, the message becomes its args |\n| `-c`, `--continue` | boolean | Continue the last session in this project |\n| `-s`, `--session` | string | Continue a specific session id |\n| `--fork` | boolean | Fork before continuing — requires `--continue` or `--session` |\n| `--share` | boolean | Publish a shareable URL for this session |\n| `-m`, `--model` | string | Provider/model selector — e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` |\n| `--agent` | string | Agent slug (loads from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md`) |\n| `--format` | enum | `default` (formatted) or `json` (raw event stream) |\n| `-f`, `--file` | array | Attach files to the message |\n| `--title` | string | Session title (truncated message used when omitted) |\n| `--attach` | string | Attach to a running OpenCode server URL |\n| `-p`, `--password` | string | Basic auth password (or `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD`) |\n| `--dir` | string | Working directory or remote-server path |\n| `--port` | number | Local server port (random when omitted) |\n| `--variant` | string | Provider-specific reasoning effort (`high`, `max`, `minimal`, etc.) |\n| `--thinking` | boolean | Show thinking blocks (default false) |\n\n> **`--command` semantics (verified on v1.17.4):** the `run` message is plain text — slash-command syntax inside it (`opencode run \"/memory:search query\"`) is NOT expanded, so the command's template never reaches the model. Executing a registered command non-interactively requires `--command <family>/<name>` with the args as the message (they become `$ARGUMENTS`). Registry names are slash-namespaced (`memory/search` for `/memory:search`); a wrong name fails with the full registry list. Behavior probes of slash commands MUST use `--command`; the raw-text form only measures the model freestyling without the contract. Consequences: (a) any behavior/adherence probe of a slash command MUST use `--command`, and the raw-text form is only valid as a labeled negative control; (b) inside `` !`…` `` template injections `$ARGUMENTS` expands like `\"$@\"` — one word per argument — so renderer scripts must join argv themselves.\n\n### cli-opencode default invocation shape\n\nThe skill builds every dispatch from a base shape and overlays use-case-specific flags:\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent <agent-slug> \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt>\"\n```\n\n| Flag | Default | Reason |\n|------|---------|--------|\n| `--model` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Direct DeepSeek is the default provider — elevated reasoning at low cost; operator may override (e.g. `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash`, `kimi-for-coding/k2p7`, or any live OpenAI GPT-5.6 slug: `openai/gpt-5.6`, `openai/gpt-5.6-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-terra-pro`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-fast`, `openai/gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) |\n| `--agent` | per use case | Required for use case 1 / 3; optional for use case 2 |\n| `--variant high` | high | Routine cli-opencode dispatches benefit from elevated reasoning effort |\n| `--format json` | json | Structured event stream is what external runtimes parse |\n| `--dir` | repo root | Pin the working directory to avoid CWD ambiguity |\n\n### Stdin handling — `</dev/null` is required for non-interactive dispatch\n\n> **opencode v1.14.39 reads stdin at startup before session creation.** If you redirect stdout/stderr to files in automation (`> stdout.log 2> stderr.log`), opencode hangs at 0% CPU after the `+60s snapshot prune cleanup` log line because stdin remains attached to the parent terminal and never receives EOF.\n\nALWAYS append `</dev/null` AFTER the prompt argument and BEFORE the stdout/stderr redirects:\n\n```bash\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n#                                  ^^^^^^^^^^\n#                                  redirects stdin from /dev/null → immediate EOF\n```\n\nForeground `| tail` accidentally works because the upstream pipe stage provides closed stdin, but `> file 2> file` does not. See `references/integration_patterns.md` §6 for the full failure-mode + fix matrix and `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 for the discovery context.\n\n### Sessions, share URLs, and ports\n\n`--share` publishes the session over the OpenCode share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). External-runtime dispatches do NOT publish share URLs by default.\n\n`--port` only matters when the dispatch needs to bind a known port (e.g. for a parallel detached session that another tool will attach to). The default random port is correct for one-shot dispatches.\n\n`--continue` and `--session <id>` reuse prior session state. `--fork` branches an existing session into a new one. cli-opencode uses session continuation in memory handback flows where the calling AI wants to thread context across multiple delegations.\n\n### Provider Auth Pre-Flight (smart fallback)\n\nBefore the first dispatch in a session, run a one-shot auth pre-flight against `opencode providers list` so a missing default doesn't fail mid-dispatch. Cache the result for the session; only re-run on auth failure.\n\n```bash\n# Pre-flight — one call per session\nPROVIDERS=$(opencode providers list 2>&1)\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"deepseek\"            && DEEPSEEK_OK=1       || DEEPSEEK_OK=0\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"minimax-coding-plan\" && MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1  || MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0   # MiniMax Token Plan (default MiniMax path)\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"minimax([^-]|$)\"    && MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1 || MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0  # MiniMax Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the coding-plan provider\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -q \"xiaomi-token-plan-ams\" && XIAOMI_OK=1       || XIAOMI_OK=0          # Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\necho \"$PROVIDERS\" | grep -qE \"xiaomi([^-]|$)\"     && XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1 || XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0   # Xiaomi Direct API (pay-per-token); regex skips the token-plan-ams provider\necho \"default=$DEEPSEEK_OK minimax_token=$MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK minimax_direct=$MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK xiaomi=$XIAOMI_OK xiaomi_direct=$XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK\"\n```\n\n| State | DEEPSEEK_OK | Action |\n|-------|-------------|--------|\n| Default available | 1 | Proceed with `--model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro --variant high` |\n| Default missing | 0 | **ASK user** before substituting (offer A: openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro, B: login deepseek and retry, C: name a different model) — do not dispatch until configured |\n\n**MiniMax routing** (default = Token Plan; Direct API is the pay-per-token alternative):\n\n| State | Condition | Action |\n|-------|-----------|--------|\n| MiniMax requested (default) | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` — **omit `--agent`** (rejected on opencode 1.15.13) |\n| Token Plan not configured | `MINIMAX_TOKEN_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → MiniMax Token Plan — never substitute silently |\n| Direct API explicitly requested | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model minimax/MiniMax-M3` (pay-per-token; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax`) |\n| Direct API requested, not configured | `MINIMAX_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to configure the `minimax` provider (`MINIMAX_API_KEY`) — do not substitute silently |\n\n**MiMo routing** (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe and Xiaomi Direct API; explicitly-selectable — first match wins):\n\n| State | Condition | Action |\n|-------|-----------|--------|\n| MiMo requested (default) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` — **omit `--agent`** (`--agent general` warns and falls back on opencode 1.15.13). Confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n| MiMo speed variant (\"ultraspeed\", latency-sensitive) | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` — low-latency MiMo-V2.5-Pro tier, same prompt contract |\n| Token Plan explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_OK=1` | `--model xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` — NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead |\n| Token Plan not configured | `XIAOMI_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode auth login` → Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — never substitute silently |\n| Direct API explicitly requested | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=1` | Proceed with `--model xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` or `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed` (pay-per-token; confirm live ids via `opencode models xiaomi`) |\n| Direct API requested, not configured | `XIAOMI_DIRECT_OK=0` | **ASK user** to run `opencode providers login xiaomi` — never substitute silently |\n\n**Login / setup command shapes** (the AI surfaces these to the user; the user runs them in their own terminal):\n\n```bash\n# Recommended default — direct DeepSeek API\nopencode providers login deepseek\n\n# MiniMax Token Plan — DEFAULT MiniMax path (subscription). Interactive: pick \"MiniMax Token Plan (minimax.io)\".\nopencode auth login          # → provider minimax-coding-plan; Anthropic-compatible https://api.minimax.io/anthropic/v1 (China: api.minimaxi.com)\n\n# MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative (needs MINIMAX_API_KEY; platform endpoint https://api.minimax.io/v1)\nopencode providers login minimax\n\n# Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — provider-managed endpoint. Interactive: pick \"Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\".\nopencode auth login          # → provider xiaomi-token-plan-ams (Xiaomi Token Plan, Europe)\n\n# Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token alternative\nopencode providers login xiaomi\n\n# Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM coding subscription. Interactive: pick \"Z.AI Coding Plan\".\nopencode auth login          # → provider zai-coding-plan; model zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2\n```\n\n> Do not mix region endpoints (international `minimax.io` vs China `minimaxi.com`). Confirm live model ids with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan`. The Xiaomi endpoint is provider-managed (no documented base URL — do not invent one); confirm live model ids with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Token Plan) or `opencode models xiaomi` (Direct API).\n\n**On auth-error mid-dispatch** (`401 Unauthorized`, `provider/model not found`): invalidate the cache, rerun the pre-flight, and apply the same decision tree before retrying. Never substitute a model the user didn't approve.\n\n### User-facing prompt templates\n\nSurface these verbatim to the operator when the pre-flight decision tree lands on \"ASK user\" (default missing with a fallback configured, or all providers missing). Never dispatch until the operator responds.\n\n**Default missing, fallback configured:**\n\n```text\nThe skill default `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` is not configured on this machine.\nA configured fallback is available. Pick one:\n  A) Use `openai/gpt-5.6-sol-pro --variant high` (OpenAI premium, configured now — paid)\n  B) Use `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro --variant high` (Xiaomi Direct API, configured now) — or `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed --variant high` for latency-sensitive runs\n  C) Use `kimi-for-coding/k2p7` (Kimi For Coding plan, configured now — subscription)\n  D) Run `opencode providers login deepseek` first, then retry the original dispatch\n  E) Name a different model — paste the `--model <provider/model>` you want to use\n```\n\n**All providers missing:**\n\n```text\nNo supported providers are configured on this machine. Run one:\n  - `opencode providers login deepseek`     (recommended — default for cli-opencode)\n  - `opencode auth login`                   (MiniMax Token Plan — default MiniMax path; pick \"MiniMax Token Plan (minimax.io)\" → provider minimax-coding-plan; model minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3)\n  - `opencode providers login minimax`      (MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token; needs MINIMAX_API_KEY; model minimax/MiniMax-M3)\n  - `opencode auth login`                   (Xiaomi Token Plan — default Xiaomi path; pick \"Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe)\" → provider xiaomi-token-plan-ams; model xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro)\n  - `opencode providers login xiaomi`       (Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token; models xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro and xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed)\n  - `opencode auth login`                   (Kimi For Coding plan — Kimi/Moonshot coding subscription; provider kimi-for-coding; model kimi-for-coding/k2p7)\n  - `opencode auth login`                   (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM coding subscription; provider zai-coding-plan; model zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2)\n  - `opencode providers login openai`       (OpenAI premium alternative — paid)\nWhich would you like to set up? Confirm when login finishes; the skill will retry the original dispatch.\n```\n\n**Error-recovery contract.** If a dispatch returns an auth error after pre-flight passed (credential expired or rotated), invalidate the cache, rerun the pre-flight, and apply the same decision tree before retrying. Never substitute a model the user didn't approve.\n\n---\n\n## 5. MODEL SELECTION\n\nOpenCode resolves models through configured providers. The cli-opencode skill supports `deepseek` (default), `minimax-coding-plan` (MiniMax Token Plan — default MiniMax path), `minimax` (MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative), `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (Xiaomi Token Plan Europe — MiMo, explicitly-selectable; NOTE: observed not resolving on this install 2026-06-11 (ProviderModelNotFoundError surfaced as 'Unexpected server error'); re-auth via `opencode auth login` or use the `xiaomi` Direct API instead), and `xiaomi` (Xiaomi Direct API — MiMo: `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` + low-latency `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, pay-per-token) — confirmed against `opencode providers list` and `opencode models`. Run `opencode models [provider]` for the full live list on a given install.\n\n| Provider | Example model id | Use case |\n|----------|------------------|----------|\n| `deepseek` (DEFAULT) | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro` | Default — deep reasoning at low cost via direct DeepSeek API |\n| `deepseek` | `deepseek/deepseek-v4-flash` | Latency-optimized direct-API sibling |\n| `kimi-for-coding` | `kimi-for-coding/k2p7` | Long-context Kimi K2.7 Code (256k; subscription plan) |\n| `zai-coding-plan` | `zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2` | Z.AI GLM Coding Plan — GLM-5.2 flagship long-horizon coding (1M context; subscription); omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models zai-coding-plan` |\n| `minimax-coding-plan` (DEFAULT MiniMax) | `minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Token Plan (subscription) — default MiniMax dispatch; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models minimax-coding-plan` |\n| `minimax` | `minimax/MiniMax-M3` | MiniMax Direct API — pay-per-token alternative; needs `MINIMAX_API_KEY`; confirm the live id via `opencode models minimax` |\n| `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` | `xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Token Plan (Europe) — MiMo-V2.5-Pro: 1M-token context, strongly agentic (1000+ tool calls), token-efficient; omit `--agent`; verify with `opencode models xiaomi-token-plan-ams` |\n| `xiaomi` | `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro` | Xiaomi Direct API — pay-per-token; MiMo-V2.5-Pro; confirm the live id via `opencode models xiaomi` |\n\n`opencode models <provider>` lists every model id the provider exposes. The model string passed to `--model` is always `provider/model-id`.\n\n### Reasoning effort via `--variant`\n\nThe `--variant` flag maps to provider-specific reasoning effort. Underlying-model conventions apply per provider routing.\n\n| Provider | Variant values |\n|----------|----------------|\n| `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-pro`) | reasoning effort accepted |\n| `deepseek` (`deepseek-v4-flash`) | non-reasoning — `--variant` ignored |\n| `minimax-coding-plan` / `minimax` (MiniMax-M3) | `--variant` behavior unverified — omitted by default; confirm against the MiniMax API before relying on it |\n| `xiaomi-token-plan-ams` (mimo-v2.5-pro) | `--variant` maps to MiMo reasoning effort (low/medium/high); **always use `--variant high`** (confirmed accepted on opencode 1.15.13) |\n| `zai-coding-plan` (glm-5.2) | GLM has native `reasoning_effort` (high/max); whether opencode `--variant` forwards to it is unverified — smoke-test before relying on it |\n| `openai` GPT-5.6 (`gpt-5.6` / `gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`) | `--variant` maps to OpenAI reasoning effort — a separate lever from the model tier: `none`/`low`/`medium`/`high`/**`xhigh`** (Pro tiers — `gpt-5.6-pro` / `gpt-5.6-sol-pro` / `gpt-5.6-terra-pro` / `gpt-5.6-luna-pro`: `medium`/`high`/`xhigh` — **inferred from the now-retired `gpt-5.5-pro` mapping and unverified against the live catalog (which no longer lists `gpt-5.5-pro` to re-check); smoke-test a Pro slug at `--variant low` before relying on the restriction**). **The `-fast` slugs** (`gpt-5.6-fast` / `gpt-5.6-sol-fast` / `gpt-5.6-terra-fast` / `gpt-5.6-luna-fast`) are the low-latency **Fast** model tier (OpenAI `priority` service tier) with the same effort range — e.g. `--model openai/gpt-5.6-sol-fast --variant xhigh`. `gpt-5.6-sol` is the flagship default; confirm live slugs via `opencode models openai`. |\n\nDefault skill behavior: pass `--variant high` for cross-AI dispatches. Operators may override via the prompt template's variant field.\n\n### Model-specific operational caveats\n\n- **Kimi K2.7 Code (`kimi-for-coding/k2p7`) over-exploration (observed 2026-06-17):** on broad / large-repo scopes at `--variant high`, k2p7 over-explores (many sequential reads) and can exceed a 600s timeout WITHOUT emitting — opencode flushes only the final assistant message to stdout, so a killed run yields 0 bytes (looks like a hang, but it was working). Mitigate with a hard read-cap in the prompt (\"read ≤N files then emit\") + a 1200s+ timeout, or omit `--variant`.\n- **GLM-5.2 (`zai-coding-plan/glm-5.2`) latency variance (benchmark 008, n=45):** thinking-on drives latency variance 6–161s (avg ~26s) — budget generous timeouts; expect ~1/45 transient dispatch failures (retry the cell). Empirical prompt framework: COSTAR (benchmark 008).\n- **GLM-5.2 vision (image input):** `glm-5.2` is natively multimodal (vision-to-code), but `opencode run --file <image>` does NOT deliver images to this provider — upstream #20802 for custom OpenAI-compatible providers (confirmed 2026-06-28: `--file` → `NO_IMAGE_RECEIVED`). For image input use the direct Z.AI Coding Plan multimodal API (base64 `image_url` at `https://api.z.ai/api/coding/paas/v4/chat/completions`) — a deviation from this skill's dispatch path justified only by the verified #20802 breakage; see `../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md` §7.\n\n---\n\n## 6. AGENT FLAG\n\n`--agent <slug>` loads an agent definition from `.opencode/agents/<slug>.md` (project-local) or the user-level fallback. The agent definition's frontmatter pins the model, tool permissions, and system prompt that shape the dispatch.\n\n### Discovering agents\n\n| Command | What it shows |\n|---------|---------------|\n| `opencode agent list` | All registered agent slugs across project + user scopes |\n| `opencode debug agent <slug>` | Resolved frontmatter and system prompt for a slug |\n| `opencode debug skill <slug>` | Skill resolution for a slug if the agent loads one |\n\n### Agent slugs in this repo\n\n| Slug | Role |\n|------|------|\n| `general` | Implementation, default subagent |\n| `context` | Read-only retrieval and search |\n| `orchestrate` | Multi-agent coordination |\n| `write` | Documentation generation |\n| `review` | Code review and PR analysis |\n| `debug` | Fresh-perspective debugging |\n| `deep-research` | Iterative research loop executor |\n| `deep-review` | Iterative code review loop executor |\n| `ai-council` | Multi-strategy planning |\n| `deep-improvement` | Agent improvement proposal mutator |\n\nThe cli-opencode skill defers to the calling AI on agent selection — see `references/agent_delegation.md` for the routing matrix and `assets/prompt_templates.md` for canonical invocation shapes.\n\n---\n\n## 7. OUTPUT FORMAT AND EVENT STREAM\n\n`--format default` produces a human-formatted log. `--format json` emits a newline-delimited JSON event stream.\n\n### JSON event shape (v1.3.17)\n\nEach line is a JSON object with at minimum:\n\n| Field | Meaning |\n|-------|---------|\n| `type` | Event type (`session.started`, `message.delta`, `tool.call`, `tool.result`, `session.completed`, ...) |\n| `timestamp` | ISO 8601 UTC timestamp |\n| `session_id` | The session id assigned by OpenCode |\n| `payload` | Type-specific payload |\n\nExternal runtimes parse the stream incrementally to surface tool calls, partial messages, and the final summary. cli-opencode prompt templates always pass `--format json` so the calling AI parses structured events instead of guessing format boundaries.\n\n---\n\n## 8. STATE LOCATION AND SHARE URLS\n\n### State directory\n\nOpenCode persists session state in a shared SQLite database and storage tree under `~/.local/share/opencode/`:\n\n- `opencode.db` (`-shm`/`-wal` companions) — the session/message database\n- `storage/` — per-session structured artifacts\n- `snapshot/` — working-tree snapshots\n\nThere is no per-session directory under `~/.opencode/state/<session_id>/` on a standard install — that path does not exist on this runtime layout. To inspect a specific session, use `opencode export <session_id>` (§3) rather than reading files from a state directory. The cli-opencode self-invocation guard's Layer 3 lock-file probe (`~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock`, per ADR-001) targets the older path as a best-effort third layer on top of the env-var and process-ancestry checks; treat it as a heuristic, not a verified-present artifact, on installs where `~/.opencode/state/` does not exist.\n\n### Share URLs\n\n`--share` publishes a session URL via OpenCode's share infrastructure. The skill ONLY appends `--share` for use case 2 (in-OpenCode parallel detached sessions). The CHK-033 P1 checklist item requires operator confirmation before publishing a share URL because the URL exposes the session contents.\n\n---\n\n## 9. VERSION DRIFT\n\nThis reference is pinned to OpenCode v1.3.17. If the live binary reports a different version, do the following:\n\n1. Run `opencode run --help` and diff the flag list against Section 4.\n2. Run `opencode --help` and diff the subcommand list against Section 3.\n3. If a flag was renamed, prefer the new name in the dispatch. If a flag was removed, fall back to the closest analogue and surface the drift in the calling AI's response.\n4. If the operator's machine has a major version bump (v1.4+, v2.x), re-validate the entire skill against the new flag table and bump the cli-opencode minor version.\n\n### Failure modes specific to drift\n\n| Symptom | Likely cause |\n|---------|--------------|\n| `unknown option --variant` | v1.2 or earlier — variant flag was named `--reasoning` |\n| `unknown option --share` | Older standalone build without share infrastructure |\n| `unknown option --format json` | v1.0 — JSON event stream was the default and the flag did not exist |\n| `MODULE_NOT_FOUND` | Plugin loader crash; rerun with `--pure` to bypass plugins |\n\n---\n\n## 10. TROUBLESHOOTING\n\n| Symptom | Cause | Fix |\n|---------|-------|-----|\n| `command not found: opencode` | Binary not on PATH | Install via standalone installer or `brew install opencode` |\n| `OPENCODE_SERVER_PASSWORD required` | Server enforces basic auth | Pass `-p <password>` or set the env var |\n| `provider/model not found` | Provider not configured | Run `opencode providers` to enumerate, then `auth login <provider>` |\n| Empty output stream | `--format default` with non-TTY parent | Pass `--format json` and parse the event stream |\n| Session never finishes | Tool call hung | Run `opencode export <session_id>` and inspect the message log it returns |\n| Plugin load crash | Misconfigured plugin | Rerun with `--pure` to bypass all plugins |\n| Self-invocation refused | cli-opencode detected an in-OpenCode runtime | Use a sibling cli-* skill or a fresh shell session — see ADR-001 |\n| `--share` URL leaks | Share infrastructure published a session containing secrets | Operator MUST confirm before publishing per CHK-033 |\n\n---\n\n## 11. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- `./integration_patterns.md` - The three documented use cases and their copy-paste invocation shapes\n- `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix and invocation patterns\n- `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique capabilities (full plugin/skill/MCP runtime, parallel detached sessions)\n- `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste prompt templates per use case\n- `../assets/prompt_quality_card.md` - Framework selection and CLEAR 5-check\n- `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":418,"totalLines":418,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/cli_reference.md","time":{"start":1784371314916,"end":1784371314925}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07f247c42514d540016a5b58726a8081918a2609ede5d40cc9"}},"id":"prt_f74d180b3001iL0tTBvRZSUl42","sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","messageID":"msg_f74d139cd001NFObtvGUjJPKQB"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784371314957,"sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ZlQ3JoW24DEEgY3TAwcCp9WC","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n3: description: Fast-path prompt discipline for OpenCode CLI dispatches; frameworks and CLEAR are canonical in sk-prompt.\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"opencode prompt quality card\"\n6:   - \"opencode model overrides\"\n7:   - \"minimax tidd-ec dense pre-plan\"\n8:   - \"mimo costar lean prompt\"\n9:   - \"opencode dispatch framework precedence\"\n10: importance_tier: normal\n11: contextType: planning\n12: version: 1.3.0.21\n13: ---\n14: \n15: # OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n16: \n17: Fast-path dispatch discipline for `opencode run` prompts. The 7-framework table, task-to-framework map, pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are owned by the canonical card — do not inline them here.\n18: \n19: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n20: \n21: ### Purpose\n22: \n23: This card is the OpenCode CLI fast-path prompt-quality reference; it delegates the framework table + CLEAR check to the canonical card and records only OpenCode-specific model overrides plus the precedence rule.\n24: \n25: ### Usage\n26: \n27: Compose a dispatch prompt by starting from the shared layer (canonical card), applying the OpenCode model overrides, and following the precedence rule.\n28: \n29: ---\n30: \n31: ## 2. SHARED LAYER (DELEGATED — DO NOT INLINE)\n32: \n33: The 7-framework selection table, the task->framework map, the pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are OWNED by the canonical card. Do NOT copy them here.\n34: \n35: -> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md`  (deep theory: `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-improve/references/patterns_evaluation.md`)\n36: \n37: ---\n38: \n39: ## 3. OPENCODE MODEL OVERRIDES\n40: \n41: OpenCode dispatches the MiniMax, MiMo, DeepSeek-v4-pro, and Kimi-K2.7 small models, which override or default against the cross-model defaults from the canonical card:\n42: \n43: | Model (dispatchable here) | Override | Profile |\n44: |---|---|---|\n45: | MiniMax M3 (Token Plan default) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n46: | MiniMax M3 (Direct API) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n47: | MiMo V2.5 Pro (Token Plan) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n48: | MiMo V2.5 Pro (Direct API) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n49: | MiMo V2.5 Pro UltraSpeed (Direct API, low-latency) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n50: | GLM-5.2 (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan) | COSTAR + lean (empirical, benchmark 008) | [`glm-5.2.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md) |\n51: | deepseek-v4-pro / kimi-k2.7-code | default RCAF (no model-specific benchmark; shared default-unverified note) | [`deepseek-v4-pro.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/deepseek-v4-pro.md) · [`kimi-k2.7-code.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/kimi-k2.7-code.md) |\n52: \n53: **Executor notes:** Omit `--agent` for all small-model dispatches listed above. OpenCode maps `--variant low/medium/high` to MiMo's reasoning effort; `high` is the standing default for MiMo. MiniMax Token Plan (`minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3`) and Direct API (`minimax/MiniMax-M3`) both serve M3. Xiaomi Token Plan (`xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro`) and Direct API (`xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro`) both serve MiMo-V2.5-Pro; the Direct API additionally serves `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, a low-latency tier with the same prompt contract. Ambiguous use-case (1 vs 2 vs 3) prevents the router from picking a path — resolve before dispatch. Always include a self-invocation guard signal when the dispatched session could loop back.\n54: \n55: ---\n56: \n57: ## 4. DELEGATION / PRECEDENCE\n58: \n59: The 3-tier precedence rule (fast path -> model override -> deep path) is canonical in `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` and restated in `../SKILL.md`.\n60: \n61: OpenCode-specific escalation example: if the task would otherwise need a long `opencode run` prompt plus an explicit Memory Epilogue and a parallel-session decision, ask `@prompt-improver` for the final `ENHANCED_PROMPT` first, then pass that result to OpenCode.\n62: \n63: ---\n64: \n65: ## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n66: \n67: -> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` · `./prompt_templates.md` · `../SKILL.md` · `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/` (per-model profiles)\n\n(End of file - total 67 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\ndescription: Fast-path prompt discipline for OpenCode CLI dispatches; frameworks and CLEAR are canonical in sk-prompt.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode prompt quality card\"\n  - \"opencode model overrides\"\n  - \"minimax tidd-ec dense pre-plan\"\n  - \"mimo costar lean prompt\"\n  - \"opencode dispatch framework precedence\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: planning\nversion: 1.3.0.21\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n\nFast-path dispatch discipline for `opencode run` prompts. The 7-framework table, task-to-framework map, pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are owned by the canonical card — do not inline them here.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md","text":"---\ntitle: OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\ndescription: Fast-path prompt discipline for OpenCode CLI dispatches; frameworks and CLEAR are canonical in sk-prompt.\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode prompt quality card\"\n  - \"opencode model overrides\"\n  - \"minimax tidd-ec dense pre-plan\"\n  - \"mimo costar lean prompt\"\n  - \"opencode dispatch framework precedence\"\nimportance_tier: normal\ncontextType: planning\nversion: 1.3.0.21\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI — Prompt Quality Card\n\nFast-path dispatch discipline for `opencode run` prompts. The 7-framework table, task-to-framework map, pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are owned by the canonical card — do not inline them here.\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\n### Purpose\n\nThis card is the OpenCode CLI fast-path prompt-quality reference; it delegates the framework table + CLEAR check to the canonical card and records only OpenCode-specific model overrides plus the precedence rule.\n\n### Usage\n\nCompose a dispatch prompt by starting from the shared layer (canonical card), applying the OpenCode model overrides, and following the precedence rule.\n\n---\n\n## 2. SHARED LAYER (DELEGATED — DO NOT INLINE)\n\nThe 7-framework selection table, the task->framework map, the pre-planning-density / bundle-gate / anti-hallucination notes, and the CLEAR 5-question check are OWNED by the canonical card. Do NOT copy them here.\n\n-> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md`  (deep theory: `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-improve/references/patterns_evaluation.md`)\n\n---\n\n## 3. OPENCODE MODEL OVERRIDES\n\nOpenCode dispatches the MiniMax, MiMo, DeepSeek-v4-pro, and Kimi-K2.7 small models, which override or default against the cross-model defaults from the canonical card:\n\n| Model (dispatchable here) | Override | Profile |\n|---|---|---|\n| MiniMax M3 (Token Plan default) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n| MiniMax M3 (Direct API) | TIDD-EC + dense | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/minimax-m3.md` |\n| MiMo V2.5 Pro (Token Plan) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n| MiMo V2.5 Pro (Direct API) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n| MiMo V2.5 Pro UltraSpeed (Direct API, low-latency) | COSTAR + lean, `--variant high` | `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/mimo-v2.5-pro.md` |\n| GLM-5.2 (Z.AI GLM Coding Plan) | COSTAR + lean (empirical, benchmark 008) | [`glm-5.2.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/glm-5.2.md) |\n| deepseek-v4-pro / kimi-k2.7-code | default RCAF (no model-specific benchmark; shared default-unverified note) | [`deepseek-v4-pro.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/deepseek-v4-pro.md) · [`kimi-k2.7-code.md`](../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/kimi-k2.7-code.md) |\n\n**Executor notes:** Omit `--agent` for all small-model dispatches listed above. OpenCode maps `--variant low/medium/high` to MiMo's reasoning effort; `high` is the standing default for MiMo. MiniMax Token Plan (`minimax-coding-plan/MiniMax-M3`) and Direct API (`minimax/MiniMax-M3`) both serve M3. Xiaomi Token Plan (`xiaomi-token-plan-ams/mimo-v2.5-pro`) and Direct API (`xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro`) both serve MiMo-V2.5-Pro; the Direct API additionally serves `xiaomi/mimo-v2.5-pro-ultraspeed`, a low-latency tier with the same prompt contract. Ambiguous use-case (1 vs 2 vs 3) prevents the router from picking a path — resolve before dispatch. Always include a self-invocation guard signal when the dispatched session could loop back.\n\n---\n\n## 4. DELEGATION / PRECEDENCE\n\nThe 3-tier precedence rule (fast path -> model override -> deep path) is canonical in `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` and restated in `../SKILL.md`.\n\nOpenCode-specific escalation example: if the task would otherwise need a long `opencode run` prompt plus an explicit Memory Epilogue and a parallel-session decision, ask `@prompt-improver` for the final `ENHANCED_PROMPT` first, then pass that result to OpenCode.\n\n---\n\n## 5. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n-> `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/assets/cli_prompt_quality_card.md` · `./prompt_templates.md` · `../SKILL.md` · `../../../sk-prompt/prompt-models/references/models/` (per-model profiles)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":67,"totalLines":67,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/assets/prompt_quality_card.md","time":{"start":1784371314952,"end":1784371314956}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07f247c42514d540016a5b58726a888191bab4123367f65716"}},"id":"prt_f74d180e6001MLEw2cPR3Om6qX","sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","messageID":"msg_f74d139cd001NFObtvGUjJPKQB"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1784371314991,"sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_lPQSDlhG3KBZj8kzkUJlUI3Q","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md"},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: ---\n2: title: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\n3: description: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\n4: trigger_phrases:\n5:   - \"opencode integration patterns\"\n6:   - \"opencode self-invocation guard\"\n7:   - \"opencode parallel detached session\"\n8:   - \"opencode cross-ai handback\"\n9:   - \"opencode stdin dev null rule\"\n10:   - \"opencode run hang non-interactive\"\n11: importance_tier: important\n12: contextType: implementation\n13: version: 1.3.0.14\n14: ---\n15: \n16: # OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n17: \n18: How cli-opencode positions itself relative to the three sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n19: \n20: ---\n21: \n22: ## 1. OVERVIEW\n23: \n24: The three sibling cli-* skills exist because their target binaries are external runtimes — Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot do not own this repo. OpenCode owns this repo. A naive \"delegate to opencode\" skill makes no sense for an in-OpenCode operator (it would create a circular dispatch).\n25: \n26: cli-opencode resolves this by documenting THREE orthogonal use cases. The smart router selects between them based on the calling AI's runtime context.\n27: \n28: | Use case | Calling runtime | Target | Self-invocation? |\n29: |----------|-----------------|--------|------------------|\n30: | 1. External runtime to OpenCode | Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell | OpenCode for full plugin / skill / MCP runtime | No |\n31: | 2. In-OpenCode parallel detached session | OpenCode itself (TUI / web / serve / acp) | New OpenCode session via `--share --port N` | No (different session id) |\n32: | 3. Cross-AI orchestration handback | OpenCode / Copilot | OpenCode for spec-kit specific workflows | No |\n33: \n34: The cycle ADR-001 protects against is the operator inside OpenCode asking cli-opencode to \"delegate this exact prompt to OpenCode\" — that case is REFUSED at the routing layer.\n35: \n36: ---\n37: \n38: ## 2. USE CASE 1 — EXTERNAL RUNTIME TO OPENCODE\n39: \n40: ### When to use\n41: \n42: The calling AI is Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, or a raw shell. The task needs the project's full plugin / skill / MCP / Spec Kit Memory runtime — not just a raw model dispatch. Examples:\n43: \n44: - Run `memory_search` against the project's spec-doc database\n45: - Call Code Graph for semantic code search across the repo\n46: - Dispatch a `@deep-research` or `@deep-review` agent loop with externalized state\n47: - Run a sub-agent that needs Spec Kit Memory for continuity across iterations\n48: \n49: ### Smart-router signal\n50: \n51: ADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (no OPENCODE_* env var, no opencode parent process, no live state lock).\n52: \n53: ### Prompt template\n54: \n55: ```text\n56: You are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into a fresh OpenCode session via cli-opencode.\n57: \n58: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n59: \n60: Context:\n61: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n62: - Plugins / skills required: <list>\n63: - MCP tools required: <list>\n64: \n65: Constraints:\n66: - <list>\n67: \n68: Success criteria:\n69: - <list>\n70: \n71: Memory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end of the response so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n72: ```\n73: \n74: ### Invocation shape\n75: \n76: ```bash\n77: opencode run \\\n78:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n79:   --agent general \\\n80:   --variant high \\\n81:   --format json \\\n82:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n83:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n84: ```\n85: \n86: ### Why it matters\n87: \n88: This is the canonical cross-AI dispatch path. It gives external runtimes a one-shot bridge into the project's full runtime without forcing the operator to leave their host session.\n89: \n90: ---\n91: \n92: ## 3. USE CASE 2 — IN-OPENCODE PARALLEL DETACHED SESSION\n93: \n94: ### When to use\n95: \n96: The operator is already inside an OpenCode session (TUI, web, serve, acp). They want a SEPARATE OpenCode session — not a continuation, not a fork — to run an ablation suite, a worker farm, or a parallel research sweep. The new session has its own session id, its own state directory, and an optional share URL.\n97: \n98: ### Smart-router signal\n99: \n100: ADR-001's detection signal trips (in-OpenCode runtime). The router checks the prompt for explicit parallel-session keywords:\n101: \n102: - \"parallel detached session\"\n103: - \"ablation suite\"\n104: - \"worker farm\"\n105: - \"parallel research\"\n106: - \"spawn detached\"\n107: - \"share URL\"\n108: \n109: If at least one of these phrases appears AND the prompt does NOT request \"delegate this exact prompt\", the router permits the dispatch with `--share --port <N>`.\n110: \n111: ### Prompt template\n112: \n113: ```text\n114: You are spawning a parallel detached OpenCode session for <purpose>.\n115: \n116: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n117: \n118: Context:\n119: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n120: - Iteration N of <total>\n121: - State file: <path>\n122: \n123: Constraints:\n124: - This session must NOT modify the parent session's state.\n125: - Write results to <state file path>.\n126: - Publish a share URL only if the operator confirmed (CHK-033).\n127: \n128: Success criteria:\n129: - <list>\n130: ```\n131: \n132: ### Invocation shape\n133: \n134: ```bash\n135: opencode run \\\n136:   --share \\\n137:   --port 4096 \\\n138:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n139:   --agent deep-research \\\n140:   --variant high \\\n141:   --format json \\\n142:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n143:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n144: ```\n145: \n146: ### Why it matters\n147: \n148: Parallel research, ablation studies, and worker farms need N concurrent sessions. Each must be independent. The detached pattern makes this possible without leaking state between sessions.\n149: \n150: ### Operator confirmation for share URLs\n151: \n152: Per CHK-033, the calling AI MUST confirm with the operator before passing `--share`. The share URL exposes the session's contents to anyone with the URL, so it is opt-in.\n153: \n154: ---\n155: \n156: ## 4. USE CASE 3 — CROSS-AI ORCHESTRATION HANDBACK\n157: \n158: ### When to use\n159: \n160: The calling AI is a non-Anthropic CLI (OpenCode, Copilot). The task requires OpenCode-specific plugins or skills (e.g. spec-kit workflows, the Spec Kit Memory MCP database, the structural code graph). The non-Anthropic CLI cannot load the project's plugins on its own — cli-opencode is the documented bridge.\n161: \n162: ### Smart-router signal\n163: \n164: ADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (the calling AI is OpenCode / Copilot, not OpenCode). The prompt mentions a project-specific subsystem:\n165: \n166: - \"spec kit\" / \"spec-kit\" / \"spec_kit\"\n167: - \"spec kit memory\"\n168: - \"code graph\"\n169: - \"skill advisor\"\n170: - \"session bootstrap\"\n171: \n172: When the calling AI is non-Anthropic AND a project-specific subsystem is named, this use case is selected over use case 1 (which is the more general path).\n173: \n174: ### Prompt template\n175: \n176: ```text\n177: You are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into OpenCode for a spec-kit-specific workflow.\n178: \n179: Goal: <one-sentence goal>\n180: \n181: Context:\n182: - Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n183: - Subsystem: <spec-kit / memory / code-graph / advisor>\n184: - Operation: <save / search / query / scan / validate>\n185: \n186: Constraints:\n187: - The OpenCode session MUST load the system-spec-kit skill for this dispatch.\n188: - All MCP calls go through the project's local MCP servers.\n189: \n190: Success criteria:\n191: - <list>\n192: \n193: Memory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n194: ```\n195: \n196: ### Invocation shape\n197: \n198: ```bash\n199: opencode run \\\n200:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n201:   --agent general \\\n202:   --variant high \\\n203:   --format json \\\n204:   --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n205:   \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n206: ```\n207: \n208: The invocation shape is identical to use case 1 — the difference is the prompt content, which targets a project-specific subsystem.\n209: \n210: ### Why it matters\n211: \n212: OpenCode and Copilot cannot load this project's plugin / skill / MCP runtime on their own. cli-opencode is the documented bridge that lets a OpenCode-led orchestration call into the project's spec-kit workflows without leaving the OpenCode session.\n213: \n214: ---\n215: \n216: ## 5. SMART-ROUTER DECISION TREE\n217: \n218: The skill's smart router picks between the three use cases (or refuses) using this decision tree:\n219: \n220: ```text\n221: INPUT: prompt + calling runtime\n222:                 |\n223:                 v\n224: [ADR-001 SELF-INVOCATION GUARD]\n225: - Layer 1: env var lookup (any OPENCODE_* env var present?)\n226: - Layer 2: process ancestry (opencode in parent process tree?)\n227: - Layer 3: best-effort lock-file probe (~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock present? -- heuristic, not guaranteed on every install)\n228:                 |\n229:         +-------+-------+\n230:         |               |\n231:        NO              YES\n232:         |               |\n233:         v               v\n234: [CALLING RUNTIME]   [PROMPT KEYWORDS]\n235:         |               |\n236:    +----+----+    +-----+-----+\n237:    |         |    |           |\n238: Anthropic  Other  parallel   self-dispatch\n239: (Claude    (OpenCode words    only\n240: Code)      Copilot)        |           |\n241:    |         |             v           v\n242:    v         v        USE CASE 2   REFUSE\n243: USE CASE  [PROJECT     (in-       (cycle —\n244: 1         SUBSYSTEM    OpenCode   surface\n245: (external NAMED?]      parallel)  ADR-001\n246: to                      |          error)\n247: OpenCode)        +------+------+\n248:                  |             |\n249:                 YES            NO\n250:                  |             |\n251:                  v             v\n252:              USE CASE 3     USE CASE 1\n253:              (cross-AI      (external\n254:              handback)      to OpenCode)\n255: ```\n256: \n257: ### Refusal message\n258: \n259: When the router hits the REFUSE leaf, it surfaces this exact message:\n260: \n261: ```text\n262: ERROR: cli-opencode self-invocation refused.\n263: \n264: You are already inside OpenCode (signal: <env|ancestry|lockfile> tripped).\n265: Asking cli-opencode to delegate this exact prompt back to OpenCode would create\n266: a circular dispatch.\n267: \n268: Options:\n269: 1. Use a sibling cli-* skill (cli-claude-code, cli-opencode)\n270:    to dispatch a different model.\n271: 2. Open a fresh shell session (no OpenCode parent) and re-run from there.\n272: 3. If you wanted a parallel detached session (different session id, separate\n273:    state directory), restate the request with explicit \"parallel detached\" /\n274:    \"ablation suite\" / \"worker farm\" / \"share URL\" keywords — that triggers\n275:    use case 2 instead of refusal.\n276: ```\n277: \n278: ---\n279: \n280: ## 6. STDIN HANDLING — `</dev/null` IS REQUIRED FOR ALL NON-INTERACTIVE DISPATCH\n281: \n282: **`opencode run` reads stdin at startup before session creation (opencode v1.14.39).** Without an explicit closed stdin, ANY non-interactive automation that redirects stdout/stderr hangs forever at 0% CPU — even with a clean tool registry, valid model, and `--pure` set. This is the third independent root cause discovered during the 027-xce-research-based-refinement deep-research run on 2026-05-08; see `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 and memory `feedback_opencode_run_requires_dev_null_stdin.md`.\n283: \n284: ### Hang symptom (diagnostic)\n285: \n286: If you see ALL of:\n287: - Process at 0% CPU after >60s\n288: - `~/.local/share/opencode/log/<timestamp>.log` last entry is `service=snapshot prune=7.days cleanup`\n289: - 0 bytes stdout, 0 bytes stderr\n290: - No TCP connections to provider\n291: - 12-min timeout fires, exit code 124\n292: \n293: …it's the stdin-startup-deadlock. Append `</dev/null`.\n294: \n295: ### Failure patterns (all hang)\n296: \n297: ```bash\n298: # WRONG #1 — file redirect without </dev/null\n299: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n300: \n301: # WRONG #2 — combined redirect via tee\n302: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n303: \n304: # WRONG #3 — background opencode in while-read loop without </dev/null\n305: while IFS= read -r line; do\n306:   opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 &\n307: done < input.jsonl\n308: # Both bugs apply: stdin-startup-read AND silent loop-stdin consumption.\n309: ```\n310: \n311: ### Fix patterns (all work)\n312: \n313: ```bash\n314: # RIGHT #1 — file redirect with </dev/null\n315: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n316: \n317: # RIGHT #2 — combined redirect with explicit closed stdin via < /dev/null\n318: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n319: \n320: # RIGHT #3 — background in while-read loop\n321: while IFS= read -r line; do\n322:   opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 </dev/null &\n323: done < input.jsonl\n324: \n325: # RIGHT #4 — foreground pipe to tail (works WITHOUT </dev/null because the empty pipe upstream provides EOF)\n326: opencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tail -15\n327: ```\n328: \n329: ### Why foreground `| tail` accidentally works\n330: \n331: When you run `opencode run \"...\" 2>&1 | tail`, the shell sets up a pipe BEFORE invoking opencode. opencode's stdin is NOT connected to your terminal — it's connected to the upstream pipe stage, which has no producer (the prompt is the positional argument, not piped via stdin). The shell closes that pipe immediately, opencode reads EOF, and startup proceeds. This is fragile — `2>&1 | tee combined.log` does NOT work because `tee` may keep the pipe open differently depending on shell + tee implementation. **Always use `</dev/null` explicitly** rather than relying on accidental pipe behavior.\n332: \n333: ### Position rule\n334: \n335: `</dev/null` belongs:\n336: - AFTER the prompt positional argument\n337: - BEFORE the `> stdout 2> stderr` redirects (or anywhere on the command line — shell parses redirects independent of position, but right-after-prompt is conventional and easiest to spot during code review)\n338: \n339: ```bash\n340: # canonical order\n341: opencode run --flags \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout 2> stderr\n342: #                              ^^^^^^^^^^\n343: #                              stdin from /dev/null (immediate EOF)\n344: ```\n345: \n346: ### Background dispatch from automation scripts (the deep-research / deep-review pattern)\n347: \n348: ```bash\n349: timeout 720 opencode run \\\n350:   --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n351:   --variant high \\\n352:   --pure \\\n353:   --dangerously-skip-permissions \\\n354:   \"$(cat prompt.md)\" \\\n355:   </dev/null \\\n356:   > \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stdout.log\" \\\n357:   2> \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stderr.log\"\n358: ```\n359: \n360: This is the pattern enforced by the 4 `if_cli_opencode` blocks in the deep-research and deep-review YAML workflow files. Any new automation that dispatches opencode MUST follow it.\n361: \n362: ### Upstream\n363: \n364: The bug is in opencode v1.14.39. The fix would be: in the `run` subcommand entrypoint, check `process.stdin.isTTY` (or equivalent) and skip the stdin read in non-interactive mode — the message is already provided as a positional argument, so stdin is informational only. Until upstream patches this, `</dev/null` at every callsite is the workaround. File a bug report with opencode-ai/opencode if not already filed.\n365: \n366: ---\n367: \n368: ## 7. MEMORY HANDBACK\n369: \n370: cli-opencode dispatches that produce evidence for a Spec Kit Memory save MUST include the Memory Epilogue at the end of the prompt. The dispatched session adds `MEMORY_HANDBACK_START` / `MEMORY_HANDBACK_END` delimiters around a structured JSON payload that the calling AI extracts and feeds to `generate-context.js`.\n371: \n372: The full Memory Handback Protocol is shared with cli-claude-code and cli-opencode. See SKILL.md Section 4 (RULES) for the canonical 7-step procedure. The same JSON normalization (camelCase / snake_case aliases) and post-010 save gates apply.\n373: \n374: ---\n375: \n376: ## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n377: \n378: - `./cli_reference.md` - Full subcommand and flag reference\n379: - `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique value props vs sibling cli-* skills\n380: - `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix\n381: - `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste templates per use case\n382: - `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router pseudocode\n\n(End of file - total 382 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\ndescription: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode integration patterns\"\n  - \"opencode self-invocation guard\"\n  - \"opencode parallel detached session\"\n  - \"opencode cross-ai handback\"\n  - \"opencode stdin dev null rule\"\n  - \"opencode run hang non-interactive\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.14\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n\nHow cli-opencode positions itself relative to the three sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n\n---","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md","text":"---\ntitle: \"OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns and Use Cases\"\ndescription: \"The three documented use cases for cli-opencode (external runtime to OpenCode, in-OpenCode parallel detached session, cross-AI orchestration handback) with copy-paste prompt templates, smart-router signals, and the self-invocation guard decision tree.\"\ntrigger_phrases:\n  - \"opencode integration patterns\"\n  - \"opencode self-invocation guard\"\n  - \"opencode parallel detached session\"\n  - \"opencode cross-ai handback\"\n  - \"opencode stdin dev null rule\"\n  - \"opencode run hang non-interactive\"\nimportance_tier: important\ncontextType: implementation\nversion: 1.3.0.14\n---\n\n# OpenCode CLI - Integration Patterns\n\nHow cli-opencode positions itself relative to the three sibling cli-* skills, the three documented use cases (per ADR-002), the smart-router decision tree that picks between them, and the self-invocation guard that protects against circular dispatch (per ADR-001).\n\n---\n\n## 1. OVERVIEW\n\nThe three sibling cli-* skills exist because their target binaries are external runtimes — Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot do not own this repo. OpenCode owns this repo. A naive \"delegate to opencode\" skill makes no sense for an in-OpenCode operator (it would create a circular dispatch).\n\ncli-opencode resolves this by documenting THREE orthogonal use cases. The smart router selects between them based on the calling AI's runtime context.\n\n| Use case | Calling runtime | Target | Self-invocation? |\n|----------|-----------------|--------|------------------|\n| 1. External runtime to OpenCode | Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, raw shell | OpenCode for full plugin / skill / MCP runtime | No |\n| 2. In-OpenCode parallel detached session | OpenCode itself (TUI / web / serve / acp) | New OpenCode session via `--share --port N` | No (different session id) |\n| 3. Cross-AI orchestration handback | OpenCode / Copilot | OpenCode for spec-kit specific workflows | No |\n\nThe cycle ADR-001 protects against is the operator inside OpenCode asking cli-opencode to \"delegate this exact prompt to OpenCode\" — that case is REFUSED at the routing layer.\n\n---\n\n## 2. USE CASE 1 — EXTERNAL RUNTIME TO OPENCODE\n\n### When to use\n\nThe calling AI is Claude Code, OpenCode, Copilot, or a raw shell. The task needs the project's full plugin / skill / MCP / Spec Kit Memory runtime — not just a raw model dispatch. Examples:\n\n- Run `memory_search` against the project's spec-doc database\n- Call Code Graph for semantic code search across the repo\n- Dispatch a `@deep-research` or `@deep-review` agent loop with externalized state\n- Run a sub-agent that needs Spec Kit Memory for continuity across iterations\n\n### Smart-router signal\n\nADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (no OPENCODE_* env var, no opencode parent process, no live state lock).\n\n### Prompt template\n\n```text\nYou are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into a fresh OpenCode session via cli-opencode.\n\nGoal: <one-sentence goal>\n\nContext:\n- Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n- Plugins / skills required: <list>\n- MCP tools required: <list>\n\nConstraints:\n- <list>\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- <list>\n\nMemory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end of the response so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n```\n\n### Invocation shape\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent general \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n```\n\n### Why it matters\n\nThis is the canonical cross-AI dispatch path. It gives external runtimes a one-shot bridge into the project's full runtime without forcing the operator to leave their host session.\n\n---\n\n## 3. USE CASE 2 — IN-OPENCODE PARALLEL DETACHED SESSION\n\n### When to use\n\nThe operator is already inside an OpenCode session (TUI, web, serve, acp). They want a SEPARATE OpenCode session — not a continuation, not a fork — to run an ablation suite, a worker farm, or a parallel research sweep. The new session has its own session id, its own state directory, and an optional share URL.\n\n### Smart-router signal\n\nADR-001's detection signal trips (in-OpenCode runtime). The router checks the prompt for explicit parallel-session keywords:\n\n- \"parallel detached session\"\n- \"ablation suite\"\n- \"worker farm\"\n- \"parallel research\"\n- \"spawn detached\"\n- \"share URL\"\n\nIf at least one of these phrases appears AND the prompt does NOT request \"delegate this exact prompt\", the router permits the dispatch with `--share --port <N>`.\n\n### Prompt template\n\n```text\nYou are spawning a parallel detached OpenCode session for <purpose>.\n\nGoal: <one-sentence goal>\n\nContext:\n- Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n- Iteration N of <total>\n- State file: <path>\n\nConstraints:\n- This session must NOT modify the parent session's state.\n- Write results to <state file path>.\n- Publish a share URL only if the operator confirmed (CHK-033).\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- <list>\n```\n\n### Invocation shape\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --share \\\n  --port 4096 \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent deep-research \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n```\n\n### Why it matters\n\nParallel research, ablation studies, and worker farms need N concurrent sessions. Each must be independent. The detached pattern makes this possible without leaking state between sessions.\n\n### Operator confirmation for share URLs\n\nPer CHK-033, the calling AI MUST confirm with the operator before passing `--share`. The share URL exposes the session's contents to anyone with the URL, so it is opt-in.\n\n---\n\n## 4. USE CASE 3 — CROSS-AI ORCHESTRATION HANDBACK\n\n### When to use\n\nThe calling AI is a non-Anthropic CLI (OpenCode, Copilot). The task requires OpenCode-specific plugins or skills (e.g. spec-kit workflows, the Spec Kit Memory MCP database, the structural code graph). The non-Anthropic CLI cannot load the project's plugins on its own — cli-opencode is the documented bridge.\n\n### Smart-router signal\n\nADR-001's detection signal does NOT trip (the calling AI is OpenCode / Copilot, not OpenCode). The prompt mentions a project-specific subsystem:\n\n- \"spec kit\" / \"spec-kit\" / \"spec_kit\"\n- \"spec kit memory\"\n- \"code graph\"\n- \"skill advisor\"\n- \"session bootstrap\"\n\nWhen the calling AI is non-Anthropic AND a project-specific subsystem is named, this use case is selected over use case 1 (which is the more general path).\n\n### Prompt template\n\n```text\nYou are dispatching from <calling-runtime> into OpenCode for a spec-kit-specific workflow.\n\nGoal: <one-sentence goal>\n\nContext:\n- Spec folder: <path> (pre-approved, skip Gate 3)\n- Subsystem: <spec-kit / memory / code-graph / advisor>\n- Operation: <save / search / query / scan / validate>\n\nConstraints:\n- The OpenCode session MUST load the system-spec-kit skill for this dispatch.\n- All MCP calls go through the project's local MCP servers.\n\nSuccess criteria:\n- <list>\n\nMemory epilogue: include MEMORY_HANDBACK delimiters at the end so the calling runtime can preserve context.\n```\n\n### Invocation shape\n\n```bash\nopencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --agent general \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --format json \\\n  --dir \"$REPO_ROOT\" \\\n  \"<prompt-from-template>\" 2>&1\n```\n\nThe invocation shape is identical to use case 1 — the difference is the prompt content, which targets a project-specific subsystem.\n\n### Why it matters\n\nOpenCode and Copilot cannot load this project's plugin / skill / MCP runtime on their own. cli-opencode is the documented bridge that lets a OpenCode-led orchestration call into the project's spec-kit workflows without leaving the OpenCode session.\n\n---\n\n## 5. SMART-ROUTER DECISION TREE\n\nThe skill's smart router picks between the three use cases (or refuses) using this decision tree:\n\n```text\nINPUT: prompt + calling runtime\n                |\n                v\n[ADR-001 SELF-INVOCATION GUARD]\n- Layer 1: env var lookup (any OPENCODE_* env var present?)\n- Layer 2: process ancestry (opencode in parent process tree?)\n- Layer 3: best-effort lock-file probe (~/.opencode/state/<id>/lock present? -- heuristic, not guaranteed on every install)\n                |\n        +-------+-------+\n        |               |\n       NO              YES\n        |               |\n        v               v\n[CALLING RUNTIME]   [PROMPT KEYWORDS]\n        |               |\n   +----+----+    +-----+-----+\n   |         |    |           |\nAnthropic  Other  parallel   self-dispatch\n(Claude    (OpenCode words    only\nCode)      Copilot)        |           |\n   |         |             v           v\n   v         v        USE CASE 2   REFUSE\nUSE CASE  [PROJECT     (in-       (cycle —\n1         SUBSYSTEM    OpenCode   surface\n(external NAMED?]      parallel)  ADR-001\nto                      |          error)\nOpenCode)        +------+------+\n                 |             |\n                YES            NO\n                 |             |\n                 v             v\n             USE CASE 3     USE CASE 1\n             (cross-AI      (external\n             handback)      to OpenCode)\n```\n\n### Refusal message\n\nWhen the router hits the REFUSE leaf, it surfaces this exact message:\n\n```text\nERROR: cli-opencode self-invocation refused.\n\nYou are already inside OpenCode (signal: <env|ancestry|lockfile> tripped).\nAsking cli-opencode to delegate this exact prompt back to OpenCode would create\na circular dispatch.\n\nOptions:\n1. Use a sibling cli-* skill (cli-claude-code, cli-opencode)\n   to dispatch a different model.\n2. Open a fresh shell session (no OpenCode parent) and re-run from there.\n3. If you wanted a parallel detached session (different session id, separate\n   state directory), restate the request with explicit \"parallel detached\" /\n   \"ablation suite\" / \"worker farm\" / \"share URL\" keywords — that triggers\n   use case 2 instead of refusal.\n```\n\n---\n\n## 6. STDIN HANDLING — `</dev/null` IS REQUIRED FOR ALL NON-INTERACTIVE DISPATCH\n\n**`opencode run` reads stdin at startup before session creation (opencode v1.14.39).** Without an explicit closed stdin, ANY non-interactive automation that redirects stdout/stderr hangs forever at 0% CPU — even with a clean tool registry, valid model, and `--pure` set. This is the third independent root cause discovered during the 027-xce-research-based-refinement deep-research run on 2026-05-08; see `../CHANGELOG-2026-05-08-tool-name-regex-fix.md` §Fix 4 and memory `feedback_opencode_run_requires_dev_null_stdin.md`.\n\n### Hang symptom (diagnostic)\n\nIf you see ALL of:\n- Process at 0% CPU after >60s\n- `~/.local/share/opencode/log/<timestamp>.log` last entry is `service=snapshot prune=7.days cleanup`\n- 0 bytes stdout, 0 bytes stderr\n- No TCP connections to provider\n- 12-min timeout fires, exit code 124\n\n…it's the stdin-startup-deadlock. Append `</dev/null`.\n\n### Failure patterns (all hang)\n\n```bash\n# WRONG #1 — file redirect without </dev/null\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n\n# WRONG #2 — combined redirect via tee\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n\n# WRONG #3 — background opencode in while-read loop without </dev/null\nwhile IFS= read -r line; do\n  opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 &\ndone < input.jsonl\n# Both bugs apply: stdin-startup-read AND silent loop-stdin consumption.\n```\n\n### Fix patterns (all work)\n\n```bash\n# RIGHT #1 — file redirect with </dev/null\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout.log 2> stderr.log\n\n# RIGHT #2 — combined redirect with explicit closed stdin via < /dev/null\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" </dev/null 2>&1 | tee combined.log\n\n# RIGHT #3 — background in while-read loop\nwhile IFS= read -r line; do\n  opencode run --format json \"<prompt>\" > \"$LOG\" 2>&1 </dev/null &\ndone < input.jsonl\n\n# RIGHT #4 — foreground pipe to tail (works WITHOUT </dev/null because the empty pipe upstream provides EOF)\nopencode run --model X \"<prompt>\" 2>&1 | tail -15\n```\n\n### Why foreground `| tail` accidentally works\n\nWhen you run `opencode run \"...\" 2>&1 | tail`, the shell sets up a pipe BEFORE invoking opencode. opencode's stdin is NOT connected to your terminal — it's connected to the upstream pipe stage, which has no producer (the prompt is the positional argument, not piped via stdin). The shell closes that pipe immediately, opencode reads EOF, and startup proceeds. This is fragile — `2>&1 | tee combined.log` does NOT work because `tee` may keep the pipe open differently depending on shell + tee implementation. **Always use `</dev/null` explicitly** rather than relying on accidental pipe behavior.\n\n### Position rule\n\n`</dev/null` belongs:\n- AFTER the prompt positional argument\n- BEFORE the `> stdout 2> stderr` redirects (or anywhere on the command line — shell parses redirects independent of position, but right-after-prompt is conventional and easiest to spot during code review)\n\n```bash\n# canonical order\nopencode run --flags \"<prompt>\" </dev/null > stdout 2> stderr\n#                              ^^^^^^^^^^\n#                              stdin from /dev/null (immediate EOF)\n```\n\n### Background dispatch from automation scripts (the deep-research / deep-review pattern)\n\n```bash\ntimeout 720 opencode run \\\n  --model deepseek/deepseek-v4-pro \\\n  --variant high \\\n  --pure \\\n  --dangerously-skip-permissions \\\n  \"$(cat prompt.md)\" \\\n  </dev/null \\\n  > \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stdout.log\" \\\n  2> \"$LOG_DIR/iter-N-stderr.log\"\n```\n\nThis is the pattern enforced by the 4 `if_cli_opencode` blocks in the deep-research and deep-review YAML workflow files. Any new automation that dispatches opencode MUST follow it.\n\n### Upstream\n\nThe bug is in opencode v1.14.39. The fix would be: in the `run` subcommand entrypoint, check `process.stdin.isTTY` (or equivalent) and skip the stdin read in non-interactive mode — the message is already provided as a positional argument, so stdin is informational only. Until upstream patches this, `</dev/null` at every callsite is the workaround. File a bug report with opencode-ai/opencode if not already filed.\n\n---\n\n## 7. MEMORY HANDBACK\n\ncli-opencode dispatches that produce evidence for a Spec Kit Memory save MUST include the Memory Epilogue at the end of the prompt. The dispatched session adds `MEMORY_HANDBACK_START` / `MEMORY_HANDBACK_END` delimiters around a structured JSON payload that the calling AI extracts and feeds to `generate-context.js`.\n\nThe full Memory Handback Protocol is shared with cli-claude-code and cli-opencode. See SKILL.md Section 4 (RULES) for the canonical 7-step procedure. The same JSON normalization (camelCase / snake_case aliases) and post-010 save gates apply.\n\n---\n\n## 8. RELATED RESOURCES\n\n- `./cli_reference.md` - Full subcommand and flag reference\n- `./opencode_tools.md` - Unique value props vs sibling cli-* skills\n- `./agent_delegation.md` - Agent routing matrix\n- `../assets/prompt_templates.md` - Copy-paste templates per use case\n- `../SKILL.md` - Skill entry point and smart router pseudocode","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":382,"totalLines":382,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/skills/cli-external-orchestration/cli-opencode/references/integration_patterns.md","time":{"start":1784371314979,"end":1784371314990}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_07f247c42514d540016a5b58726a8c81919cf031e3de8fda15"}},"id":"prt_f74d18113001JxkBxu3EMDiERX","sessionID":"ses_08b2f9e0bffesj9FY7WWisVCBE","messageID":"msg_f74d139cd001NFObtvGUjJPKQB"}}
